text: Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of alopecia mental retardation syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by an alopecia-mental retardation condition that has its material basis in variation in chromosome 18q11.2–q12.2.

Amed syndrome is a type of syndrome recognized as an autosomal recessive disease and also categorized as a digenic disease. This syndrome is based on certain autosomal recessive inheritance and digenic inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, early onset of bone marrow failure and myelodysplastic syndrome, and poor overall growth leading to short stature. The material basis for Amed syndrome lies in the homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ADH5 gene located on chromosome 4q, which must be accompanied by a specific homozygous or heterozygous allele in the ALDH2 gene (E504K) on chromosome 12q24. The presence of defects in both of these genes is necessary for the disorder to manifest, aligning with its classification as digenic inheritance. Amed syndrome is exactly synonymous with AMEDS.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1j is a type of amelogenesis imperfecta and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically falls under the category of conditions with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by an amelogenesis imperfecta that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ACPT gene located on chromosome 19q13. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with "Amelogenesis imperfecta, type IJ."

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita is a type of disorder that encompasses several classifications: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a physical disorder, and a nervous system disease. It is also defined by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Furthermore, it is characterized by the development of multiple joint contractures affecting two or more areas of the body prior to birth.

Childhood supratentorial embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes C19MC altered is a type of childhood embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes C19MC altered, which is also a type of condition that begins in childhood. It is defined as a childhood embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes, C19MC-altered, that originates in the supratentorial region of the brain and affects children.

Primary hypoalphalipoproteinemia 1 is a type of hypolipoproteinemia that is characterized by low levels of high-density lipoprotein in the blood. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ABC1 gene on chromosome 9q31, which is also the site of mutations causing Tangier disease. It is also known by its exact synonyms, familial HDL deficiency and familial hypoalphalipoproteinemia.

Primary hypoalphalipoproteinemia 2 is a type of hypolipoproteinemia, which is defined as a condition characterized by dysfunctional apoA-I production. This results in undetectable levels of apoA-I in serum and in markedly low levels of serum high density lipoprotein cholesterol. Generally, it is an autosomal recessive disorder associated with extensive atherosclerosis, xanthomas, and corneal opacities, and it has a material basis in homozygous, compound heterozygous, or heterozygous mutation in the APOA1 gene on chromosome 11q23. Furthermore, primary hypoalphalipoproteinemia 2 is also exactly synonymous with Apolipoprotein A-I deficiency.

Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia 14 is a type of arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy and autosomal dominant disease. It is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, it is defined as an arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia characterized by palpitations, chest pain, and presyncope, and it has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CDH2 gene on chromosome 18q12.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 2a6 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of amelogenesis imperfecta. It relates to conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific disorder is characterized by enamel of normal thickness that is hypomineralized, presenting a mottled appearance. The condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the G protein-coupled receptor-68 (GPR68) located on chromosome 14q32. Additionally, amelogenesis imperfecta type 2a6 is exactly synonymous with "Amelogenesis imperfecta, hypomaturation type, IIA6."

Anauxetic dysplasia 2 is a type of anauxetic dysplasia and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, indicating that it is associated with conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is specifically defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POP1 gene located on chromosome 8q22.

Anauxetic dysplasia 3 is a type of anauxetic dysplasia and an autosomal recessive disease, which is a subtype of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia characterized by severe short stature, brachydactyly, skin laxity, joint hypermobility, and joint dislocations. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the NEPRO gene located on chromosome 3q13.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 1 is a subtype of autosomal dominant disease and intracranial berry aneurysm, characterized by the material basis of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm marked by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leading to a subarachnoid hemorrhage. This sudden-onset disease can result in severe disability or death and has been mapped to chromosome 7q11.2.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 2 is a specific type of intracranial berry aneurysm. It is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm that is distinguished by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This rupture leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can result in severe disability or death. Additionally, it has been mapped to chromosome 19q13.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 3 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm and an autosomal dominant disease that essentially has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death, and it has been mapped to chromosome 1p36.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 4 is a specific type of intracranial berry aneurysm. It is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This condition leads to subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can result in severe disability and death. Furthermore, it has been mapped to chromosome 5p15.2-p14.3.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 5 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm. It is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This rupture leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death. Furthermore, it has been mapped to chromosome Xp22.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 6 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm. This condition involves an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, which leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage. Subarachnoid hemorrhage is a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death. Intracranial berry aneurysm 6 has been mapped to chromosome 9p21.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 7 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm, defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm. This rupture, an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death. Additionally, it has been mapped to chromosome 11q24-q25.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 8 is a specific type of intracranial berry aneurysm, which is defined by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm. This rupture, an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage. A subarachnoid hemorrhage is a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death. Additionally, intracranial berry aneurysm 8 has been mapped to chromosome 14q23.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 9 is a specific type of intracranial berry aneurysm. It is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This rupture leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can result in severe disability and death. Intracranial berry aneurysm 9 has been mapped to chromosome 2q33.1.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 10 is a subtype of intracranial berry aneurysm, defined by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This rupture leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can result in severe disability and death. Furthermore, it has been mapped to chromosome 8q12.1.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 11, which is a subtype of intracranial berry aneurysm, is defined as an intracranial berry aneurysm characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm. This condition, involving an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage. A subarachnoid hemorrhage is a sudden-onset disease that can result in severe disability or death, and it has been linked to chromosome 8p22.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 12 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is defined by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death. The condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the THSD1 gene located on chromosome 13q14.

Acute myeloid leukemia with BCR-ABL1 is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. It is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia characterized by blasts that harbor BCR-ABL1 translocation in the absence of a history and clinical and laboratory features of chronic myelogenous leukemia. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "Acute myeloid leukemia with BCR-ABL1."

Aortic valve disease 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of bicuspid aortic valve disease. It falls under a classification of conditions that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The disease is defined as a bicuspid aortic valve disease characterized by aortic stenosis and/or bicuspid aortic valve. Some patients may also be associated with an aneurysm of the aortic root and/or ascending aorta. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ROBO4 gene on chromosome 11q24.

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 1 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita and also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an arthrogryposis multiplex congenita that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LGI4 gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 3 is a specific type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an arthrogryposis multiplex congenita characterized by decreased fetal movements, hypotonia, variable skeletal defects such as clubfoot and scoliosis, and delayed motor milestones with difficulty walking. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SYNE1 gene located on chromosome 6q25.

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 4 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita and also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita is defined by having a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SCYL2 gene located on chromosome 12q23. Additionally, arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 4 is exactly synonymous with Zain syndrome.

Arthrogryposis Multiplex Congenita 5 is a type of Arthrogryposis Multiplex Congenita and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an Arthrogryposis Multiplex Congenita that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TOR1A gene on chromosome 9q34.

X-linked mental retardation hypotonic facies syndrome 1 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that is primarily characterized by severe mental retardation, dysmorphic facies, and a highly skewed X-inactivation pattern in carrier women. It has a material basis in mutation in the ATRX gene. This syndrome comprises several syndromes that were previously reported separately, including Carpenter-Waziri, Holmes-Gang, and Smith-Fineman-Myers syndromes. Additionally, X-linked alpha-thalassemia/mental retardation syndrome is an allelic disorder with a similar phenotype but also includes alpha-thalassemia and Hb H inclusion bodies in erythrocytes.

X-linked intellectual developmental disorder 109 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, which is also a form of X-linked recessive disease. This condition is part of a category that, at the very least, has its material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mildly to moderately impaired intellectual development associated with learning difficulties, communication deficits, attention problems, hyperactivity, and autistic behavior. The condition has its material basis in the disruption of the FMR2 gene (AFF2), either by expansion of a CCG repeat in the 5-prime untranslated region or by deletion. Additionally, X-linked intellectual developmental disorder 109 is exactly synonymous with Fragile XE syndrome and is also known as the fragile site on chromosome Xq28.

The Syndromic X-linked Intellectual Disorder Lujan Fryns type is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, categorized under X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by at least having a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and exhibiting a phenotype that includes abnormal facial shape. This disorder is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability distinguished by a tall, marfanoid stature, specific facial dysmorphism, and behavioral issues. It has its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the MED12 gene located on chromosome Xq13. Furthermore, Opitz-Kaveggia syndrome is an allelic disorder with an overlapping phenotype with this disorder.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Periodontal Type 1 is a type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It exhibits a phenotype that includes hyperextensible skin, joint hypermobility, and widened atrophic scars. This specific type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome is characterized by a severe periodontal inflammation phenotype combined with typical Ehlers Danlos Syndrome features. Its genetic basis is a heterozygous mutation in the C1R gene on chromosome 12p13. Additionally, it is described as having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Periodontal Type 2 is a type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is fundamentally characterized by a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the C1S gene located on chromosome 12p13.

Pretibial dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa is a type of epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica characterized by recurrent blistering and scarring, primarily in the pretibial area. It has a material basis in heterozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the type VII collagen gene (COL7A1) located on chromosome 3p21. The lesions often exhibit lichenoid features. Additionally, pretibial epidermolysis bullosa is allelic to both autosomal dominant and recessive dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa.

King Denborough Syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of myopathy, specifically characterized by its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined by distinct facial features, including ptosis, downslanted palpebral fissures, widely spaced eyes, epicanthal folds, low-set ears, malar hypoplasia, micrognathia, a high-arched palate, clinodactyly, a single palmar crease, pectus excavatum, winging of the scapulae, lumbar lordosis, and mild thoracic scoliosis. Moreover, pathogenic variants in RYR1 have been identified in some individuals with this syndrome. King Denborough Syndrome also has exact matches with MESH ID C536883 and OMIM ID 619542.

Congenital myopathy 1b, which is also known exactly as multiminicore disease, is a type of congenital myopathy. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by multiple areas of reduced mitochondrial oxidative activity running along a limited extent of the longitudinal axis of the muscle fiber, referred to as 'minicores'. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RYR1 gene on chromosome 19q13. Multiminicore disease is broadly classified into four groups: the classic form, moderate form with hand involvement, antenatal form with arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, and the ophthalmoplegic form.

Rhabdomyolysis myalgia syndrome is a type of myopathy and is also classified as a condition that at least has symptoms including some form of cramp. It is defined as a myopathy characterized by muscle breakdown (rhabdomyolysis), heat and exertion-related muscle pain (myalgia) and cramping symptoms, severe muscle pain, sudden elevation and subsequent fall of serum creatine phosphokinase levels, and the presence of products of muscle breakdown in the urine (myoglobinuria). This syndrome is associated with RYR1 variations. The occurrence of rhabdomyolysis can be triggered by various external factors such as strenuous exercise beyond the limit of fatigue, heat stress, illicit drug or alcohol abuse, use of supplements or certain medications, recent viral illness, or muscle trauma.

Autoimmune epilepsy is a type of epilepsy and an autoimmune disease of the central nervous system. It falls under the category of conditions that at least display a phenotype of abnormal immunoglobulin levels. Autoimmune epilepsy is defined as an epilepsy characterized by new-onset refractory seizures, accompanied by subacute progressive cognitive decline, and behavioral or psychiatric dysfunction.

Tuberculous encephalopathy is a type of tuberculosis characterized by cerebral edema, sometimes featuring similarities to acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (ADEM). It may manifest with a variety of symptoms, including focal neurological deficits, convulsions, and a decreased conscious state.

Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma Activated B Cell Type is a specific type of Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma. It is characterized by the expression of CD44, PKCbeta1, Cyclin D2, BCL-2, and IRF4/MUM1 genes. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with DLBCL ABC type.

Diffuse large B cell lymphoma germinal center B cell type is a specific type of diffuse large B cell lymphoma. This particular type is defined by its characteristic expression of CD10, BCL-6, A-myb, and LMO2 genes, the presence of BCL-2 translocation, and c-REL amplification.

Acute necrotizing pancreatitis is a type of acute pancreatitis characterized by one or more areas of necrosis in the pancreas, with varying degrees of involvement of the surrounding tissues or organ systems.

Acute hemorrhagic pancreatitis is a type of acute pancreatitis. It is defined as an acute pancreatitis characterized by acute inflammation of the pancreas in which the initial edematous pancreatitis evolves into necrosis accompanied by hemorrhage.
Cowden Syndrome 4 is a type of Cowden Syndrome, which is defined as a Cowden Syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous germline hypermethylation of the KLLN gene located on chromosome 10q23.
Cowden Syndrome 5 is a type of Cowden Syndrome that is defined as a Cowden syndrome with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PIK3CA gene located on chromosome 3q26.
Cowden syndrome 6 is a type of Cowden syndrome characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the AKT1 gene on chromosome 14q32.3.
Cowden Syndrome 7 is a type of Cowden Syndrome characterized by having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SEC23B gene located on chromosome 20p11.

High grade B cell lymphoma double hit triple hit is a type of B cell lymphoma characterized by the abnormal rearrangement of two genes, MYC gene and either BCL2 or BCL6 genes. It has the exact synonyms HGBL-DH/TH and High Grade B-Cell Lymphoma with MYC and BCL2 or BCL6 Rearrangements.
A parsley allergy, which falls under the category of vegetable allergies, is defined as a vegetable allergy triggered by parsley (Petroselinum).
Dill allergy, a type of vegetable allergy, is defined as a food allergy triggered by dill (Anethum graveolens).

RNASET2 deficient cystic leukoencephalopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a form of leukodystrophy. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a leukodystrophy characterized by a non-progressive leukoencephalopathy, with bilateral cysts located in the anterior part of the temporal lobe, anomalies in the cerebral white matter, and severe psychomotor impairment. Additionally, this condition is known by exact synonyms, including cystic leukoencephalopathy without megalencephaly and infantile-onset RNASET2 deficient cystic leukoencephalopathy.

Intellectual developmental disorder with cardiac arrhythmia is a syndrome and a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is defined by delayed psychomotor development, severe intellectual disability with poor or absent speech, and bradycardia and/or cardiac sinus arrhythmias. The material basis for this condition is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GNB5 gene on chromosome 15q21. Additionally, intellectual developmental disorder with cardiac arrhythmia is exactly synonymous with GNB5-related intellectual disability-cardiac arrhythmia syndrome.

Bardet Biedl syndrome 20 is a type of Bardet Biedl syndrome and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Bardet-Biedl syndrome characterized by rod-cone dystrophy, postaxial polydactyly, truncal obesity, renal anomalies, and learning disability, in addition to hypogonadism in males and genital abnormalities in females. This particular syndrome has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the IFT172 gene on chromosome 2p23.

Bardet Biedl Syndrome 21 is a specific type of Bardet Biedl Syndrome and is also categorized as a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular syndrome is defined by its characteristics, which include obesity, postaxial polydactyly, retinal degeneration, and mild cognitive impairment, and it is caused by a homozygous mutation in the C8ORF37 gene located on chromosome 8q22.

Bardet Biedl Syndrome 22 is a subtype of Bardet Biedl Syndrome and is characterized by retinitis pigmentosa, obesity, polydactyly, hypogonadism, and intellectual disability. This specific condition is caused by compound heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the IFT74 gene located on chromosome 9p21. Additionally, Bardet Biedl Syndrome 22 is associated with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Critical COVID-19 is a type of COVID-19 that is defined as a COVID-19 characterized by the criteria for acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), sepsis, septic shock, or other conditions that would normally require the provision of life-sustaining therapies such as mechanical ventilation (invasive or non-invasive) or vasopressor therapy.

Severe COVID-19 is a type of COVID-19 that is defined as a COVID-19 characterized by any of the following: Oxygen saturation below 90% on room air, a respiratory rate greater than 30 breaths per minute in adults and children older than 5 years, more than 60 breaths per minute in children younger than 2 months, more than 50 breaths per minute in children aged 2–11 months, and over 40 breaths per minute in children aged 1–5 years, or signs of severe respiratory distress. These distress signs include the use of accessory muscles for breathing, inability to complete full sentences, and, in children, very severe chest wall indrawing, grunting, central cyanosis, or the presence of any other general danger signs.
Non severe COVID-19, characterized by the absence of any criteria for severe or critical COVID-19, is a type of COVID-19.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also falls under the broader category of congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles. It is considered a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific disorder is defined as a congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles characterized by bilateral blepharoptosis and ophthalmoplegia, with the eyes fixed in an infraducted position approximately 20 to 30 degrees below the horizontal midline. The disease has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KIF21A gene located on chromosome 12q12.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 2 (CFEOM2) is a type of congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles and an autosomal recessive disease. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. CFEOM2 is defined as a congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles that is characterized by bilateral ptosis and restrictive ophthalmoplegia, with the globes fixed in extreme abduction (exotropia). This condition has a material basis in homozygous mutations in the ARIX gene on chromosome 11q13.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 3a is a type of autosomal dominant disease and congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles. It is defined as a congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles characterized by a variable phenotype, where individuals may not have bilateral involvement, may be able to raise the eyes above midline, or may not have blepharoptosis. This condition at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and specifically has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TUBB3 gene on chromosome 16q24.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 3c is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This particular condition is defined as a congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles characterized by congenital bilateral ptosis and limitation of the superior rectus, which has its material basis in a reciprocal translocation t(2;13)(q37.3;q12.11).

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the COL25A1 gene on chromosome 4q25.

Tukel syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles, characterized by a nonprogressive restrictive ophthalmoplegia with blepharoptosis of the right eye, and postaxial oligodactyly/oligosyndactyly of the hands, with the right hand being more severely affected than the left. It has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, Tukel syndrome is exactly synonymous with congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 4.

Retinal cone dystrophy 3b is a type of cone dystrophy, an autosomal recessive disease, and is characterized by a specific material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a cone dystrophy characterized by onset in the first or second decade of life of very marked photophobia, myopia, reduced color vision along the red-green axis with relatively preserved tritan discrimination, and central scotomata with peripheral widespread sensitivity loss predominating in the superior visual field. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KCNV2 gene on chromosome 9p24. Additionally, retinal cone dystrophy 3b is exactly synonymous with cone dystrophy with supernormal rod responses.
Retinal cone dystrophy 4 is a type of cone dystrophy, which is defined as a cone dystrophy that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CACNA2D4 gene on chromosome 12p13.

Retinal cone dystrophy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of cone dystrophy, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a cone dystrophy characterized as an autosomal dominant form of diffuse cone degeneration.

Retinal cone dystrophy 3a is defined as a cone dystrophy characterized by reduced visual acuity, photoaversion, night blindness, and abnormal color vision. It has a material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding the gamma subunit of cone cGMP-phosphodiesterase (PDE6H) located on chromosome 12p13.
Benign peritoneal solitary fibrous tumor is a type of peritoneal benign neoplasm characterized by the presence of prominent hemangiopericytoma-like vessels.

Glycogen rich carcinoma, a type of breast adenocarcinoma, is defined as a breast adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells with abundant clear cytoplasm that contains glycogen.

Central conducting lymphatic anomaly is a type of disease that is both autosomal dominant and pertains to the lymphatic system, specifically being a lymphatic system disease that at least has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a disease characterized by the dysfunction of the thoracic duct or cisterna chyli, which leads to a retrograde flux of lymphatic fluid or abnormal drainage of lymphatic fluid, and it has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the EPHB4 gene located on chromosome 7q22. Additionally, central conducting lymphatic anomaly has the exact synonym lymphatic malformation-7.

Generalized lymphatic anomaly is a type of lymphatic system disease characterized by an abnormal overgrowth of lymphatic vessels. This condition manifests in multiple areas including the lungs, pleura, bones, and soft tissues, leading to lymphatic malformations.

Glutathione synthetase deficiency with 5-oxoprolinuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of glutathione synthetase deficiency. This condition is rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically begins during the neonatal period. It is defined by the massive urinary excretion of 5-oxoproline, metabolic acidosis, hemolytic anemia, and central nervous system damage. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding glutathione synthetase (GSS) located on chromosome 20q11. The underlying metabolic defect leads to decreased levels of cellular glutathione, which in turn overstimulates the synthesis of gamma-glutamylcysteine and its subsequent conversion to 5-oxoproline.

Mixed phenotype acute leukemia with BCR ABL1 is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia and has the exact synonym Mixed Phenotype Acute Leukemia with t(9;22)(q34.1;q11.2); BCR-ABL1. Its definition is an acute biphenotypic leukemia characterized by blasts that also carry the translocation t(9;22)(q34.1;q11.2) by karyotypic analysis or the BCR-ABL1 translocation by FISH or PCR.

Mixed phenotype acute leukemia with MLL rearranged is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia and is defined as an acute biphenotypic leukemia characterized by blasts that carry a translocation between the MLL (KMT2A) gene at 11q23.3 and another gene partner. It has the exact synonym "Mixed Phenotype Acute Leukemia with t(v;11q23.3); MLL Rearranged."

Mixed phenotype acute leukemia B myeloid is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia. It is defined as an acute biphenotypic leukemia characterized by blasts that express B-lymphoid and myeloid lineage markers but are negative for MLL translocation and t(9;22)(q34;q11.2) translocation.

Mixed phenotype acute leukemia T myeloid is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia. It is defined as an acute biphenotypic leukemia characterized by blasts that express antigens of both T and myeloid antigens.

B cell prolymphocytic leukemia is a type of prolymphocytic leukemia characterized by medium-sized, round lymphoid cells with prominent nucleoli exceeding 55% of lymphoid cells in the blood. It is also known by its exact synonyms, B Cell Prolymphocytic Leukemia and Prolymphocytic leukemia, B-cell type.

T cell prolymphocytic leukemia is a type of prolymphocytic leukemia characterized by the proliferation of small to medium-sized prolymphocytes with a mature T-cell phenotype, involving the blood, bone marrow, lymph nodes, liver, spleen, and skin. It is also known exactly as Prolymphocytic leukemia, T-cell type, and T Cell Prolymphocytic Leukemia.

Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome X-linked is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, a type of fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome that is an X-linked form characterized by brain malformations, telecanthus, and narrow palpebral fissures.
Frontonasal dysplasia is a type of syndrome characterized by a cleft in the nose, a broad nose, wide-spaced eyes, and a widow's peak.

Frontonasal dysplasia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, frontonasal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a frontonasal dysplasia characterized by features such as hypertelorism, a wide nasal bridge, broad columella, widened philtrum, widely separated narrow nares, poor development of the nasal tip, a midline notch of the upper alveolus, columella base swellings, and a low hairline. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the aristaless-like homeobox-3 gene (ALX3) on chromosome 1p13. Frontonasal dysplasia 1 also has the exact synonym "Frontorhiny."

Frontonasal dysplasia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific type of frontonasal dysplasia. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, frontonasal dysplasia 2 is defined as a frontonasal dysplasia that has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the ALX4 gene located on chromosome 11p11.

Frontonasal dysplasia 3 is a type of frontonasal dysplasia and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a frontonasal dysplasia that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the ALX1 gene on chromosome 12q21.

Congenital limbs face contractures hypotonia developmental delay syndrome, also known exactly as CLIFAHDD syndrome or congenital contractures of the limbs and face, hypotonia, and developmental delay, is a type of syndrome and a specific kind of autosomal dominant disease. This syndrome is characterized by congenital contractures of the limbs and face, resulting in characteristic facial features, hypotonia, and variable degrees of developmental delay. Its material basis is found in at least some autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically through a heterozygous mutation in the NALCN gene on chromosome 13q33.

Hepatosplenic T cell lymphoma is a type of mature T cell and NK cell lymphoma. It is defined as a mature T-cell and NK-cell lymphoma characterized by the presence of medium-size neoplastic lymphocytes infiltrating the hepatic sinusoids and originates from cytotoxic T-cells, usually of the gamma/delta T-cell type.

Primary cutaneous gamma delta T cell lymphoma is a type of primary cutaneous T cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma. It is characterized by the clonal cutaneous proliferation of activated mature gamma-delta T cells with a cytotoxic phenotype. This lymphoma is also exactly synonymous with "Primary Cutaneous Gamma-Delta T Cell Lymphomas" and "cutaneous gamma/delta T-cell lymphoma."

Microcephaly, growth deficiency, seizures, and brain malformations constitute a syndrome. This syndrome is defined as a condition characterized by intrauterine growth retardation, postnatal growth deficiency with severe microcephaly, and poor or absent psychomotor development. It has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the WDR4 gene located on chromosome 21q22.

Neurobehavioral disorder with prenatal alcohol exposure is a type of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder that is characterized by one or more deficits in neurocognition and in self-regulation, plus two or more deficits in adaptive functioning, with at least one in communication or social communication and interaction. This disorder is also a type of condition that at least has a phenotype of some neurodevelopmental abnormality and its existence starts during some pediatric onset.

Central diabetes insipidus is a type of diabetes insipidus that is characterized by symptoms such as polyuria. It is defined as a diabetes insipidus that results from a deficiency in vasopressin synthesis, leading to polyuria and polydipsia.

Gestational diabetes insipidus is a type of diabetes insipidus that is characterized by progressively rising levels of placental vasopressinase throughout pregnancy, resulting in decreased endogenous vasopressin and resulting in hypotonic polyuria worsening through the pregnancy. It is a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some polyuria. Moreover, gestational diabetes insipidus has the exact synonym transient diabetes insipidus of pregnancy.

Dipsogenic diabetes insipidus is a type of diabetes insipidus and is characterized by a condition that includes symptoms such as polyuria. It is defined as a form of diabetes insipidus that is marked by excessive thirst, polyuria with low urine osmolality, and an intact urine concentrating ability.

X-linked central diabetes insipidus is a type of X-linked monogenic disease and a type of central diabetes insipidus. It is also classified as a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. Defined as a central diabetes insipidus that has a material basis in X-linked inheritance, it has the exact synonym "X-linked neurohypophyseal diabetes insipidus."

X-linked nephrogenic diabetes insipidus is a specific type of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus and is also categorized under X-linked recessive diseases. It is a condition that primarily arises from a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. The disease is precisely defined as a form of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus characterized by the renal collecting ducts' inability to absorb water in response to antidiuretic hormone, fundamentally caused by a mutation in the gene encoding the vasopressin V2 receptor (AVPR2) on chromosome Xq28. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with nephrogenic diabetes insipidus type 1.

Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus type 2 is a type of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, and it also has an exact synonym, autosomal nephrogenic diabetes insipidus-2. This condition is characterized by the inability of the renal collecting ducts to absorb water in response to antidiuretic hormone. The basis for this disease lies in heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutations in the AQP2 gene, which encodes the aquaporin-2 water channel and is located on chromosome 12q13. Additionally, nephrogenic diabetes insipidus type 2 is identified both as an autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive disease, indicating its complex genetic inheritance patterns that include material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance.

Dicer1 syndrome is a type of syndrome that is classified as an autosomal dominant disease, which means it has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically characterized by an increased risk of developing pleuropulmonary blastoma, multinodular goiter, ovarian Sertoli-Leydig cell tumors, and/or other types of tumors. This condition occurs due to heterozygous mutation in the DICER1 gene on chromosome 14q32. The mutation affects the gene encoding the endoribonuclease, Dicer, disrupting the biogenesis and processing of miRNAs, which leads to subsequent disruption in the control of gene expression. Dicer1 syndrome is also known by exact synonyms such as PPB familial tumor susceptibility syndrome, Pleuro-pulmonary blastoma familial tumor susceptibility, Pleuro-pulmonary blastoma familial tumor susceptibility syndrome, and Pleuropulmonary blastoma familial tumor susceptibility syndrome.

BN2 diffuse large B cell lymphoma is a type of diffuse large B cell lymphoma characterized by a high probability categorization as BN2 by the LymphGen algorithm. This classification is based on a combination of genetic features. BN2 DLBCLs often, but not always, have a translocation involving the BCL6 locus and/or some combination of mutations affecting NOTCH2, TNFAIP3, BCL10, and UBE2A. Additionally, this subgroup commonly exhibits mutations due to aberrant somatic hypermutation affecting CD70, which can be coding or non-coding. BN2 diffuse large B cell lymphoma is also known by its exact synonym, BN2 DLBCL.

EZB Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma (DLBCL) is a specific type of Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma. It is defined as a DLBCL that is categorized as EZB with high probability by the LymphGen algorithm, which uses a combination of genetic features for classification. EZB DLBCLs often have hot spot mutations in EZH2 and/or a BCL2 translocation, although these are not always present. This class is further divided into two subclasses: EZB-MYC+ and EZB-MYC-, based on the double hit gene expression signature (DHITsig). Additionally, this subgroup frequently exhibits mutations due to aberrant somatic hypermutation affecting IRF8, which can be coding or non-coding. EZB Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma is also exactly synonymous with EZB DLBCL.

MCD diffuse large B cell lymphoma is a type of diffuse large B cell lymphoma and has an exact synonym, MCD DLBCL. It is defined as a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma that is categorized as MCD with high probability by the LymphGen algorithm. This categorization is based on a combination of genetic features. MCD DLBCLs often, but do not always, have the most common hot spot mutation in MYD88 (L265P) and/or activating mutations in CD79B. Additionally, this subgroup commonly has mutations due to aberrant somatic hypermutation affecting PIM1 and/or ETV6, which can be coding or non-coding.

N1 Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma is a type of Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma. It is defined as a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma that is categorized as N1 with high probability by the LymphGen algorithm, based on a combination of genetic features. Although N1 DLBCLs always have an activating mutation affecting NOTCH1, LymphGen can assign cases with this mutation to other classes, depending on the presence of other genetic features. Moreover, N1 Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma has an exact synonym, N1 DLBCL.

ST2 Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma is a specific type within the broader category of Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma. It is defined by the LymphGen algorithm as a Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma that falls into the ST2 category with a high probability, which is determined based on a combination of genetic features. Notably, ST2 DLBCLs frequently, but not invariably, exhibit missense or nonsense mutations impacting TET2 and NFKBIA. Additionally, this subgroup is characterized by common mutations resulting from aberrant somatic hypermutation that affect a variety of genes including SGK1, ZFP36L1, SOCS1, HIST1H1E, and CD83, which may involve coding or non-coding mutations. Furthermore, ST2 Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma is precisely synonymous with ST2 DLBCL.
A53 diffuse large B-cell lymphoma is a type of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma characterized by aneuploidy with TP53 inactivation. It is also exactly synonymous with A53 DLBCL.

EZB MYC diffuse large B cell lymphoma is a type of EZB diffuse large B cell lymphoma. It is defined as an EZB diffuse large B-cell lymphoma that expresses the double hit gene expression signature (DHITsig+) according to gene expression profiling. In addition to the features characteristic of EZB, these cases commonly, but do not always, harbor MYC translocations and DDX3X mutations. Moreover, EZB MYC diffuse large B cell lymphoma is exactly synonymous with EZB-MYC+ DLBCL.

EZB MYC diffuse large B cell lymphoma is a type of EZB diffuse large B cell lymphoma. It is defined as an EZB diffuse large B-cell lymphoma that does not express the double hit gene expression signature (DHITsig-) according to gene expression profiling, and these cases tend to have few MYC translocations or DDX3X mutations. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym: EZB-MYC- DLBCL.

Craniofacial dysmorphism skeletal anomalies and mental retardation syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by abnormal development of the brain and structures in the face and torso, including facial dysmorphism, intellectual deficit, costovertebral abnormalities, and delayed development of speech and movement (motor) skills. Moreover, it has exact synonyms: Cerebro-facio-thoracic dysplasia, Cerebrofaciothoracic dysplasia, Pascual-Castroviejo syndrome, and TMCO1 defect syndrome.

Teebi hypertelorism syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by hypertelorism, prominent forehead, thick eyebrows, and a short nose with broad and depressed features. It is also exactly synonymous with Brachycephalofrontonasal dysplasia.

Teebi hypertelorism syndrome 2 is a type of Teebi hypertelorism syndrome, which is defined as a Teebi hypertelorism syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CDH11 gene on chromosome 16q21.

Marsili syndrome, also known as congenital analgesia or congenital insensitivity to pain, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a lowered ability to sense pain, experience temperature, and sweat, which primarily results from a heterozygous mutation in the ZFHX2 gene on chromosome 14q11. This condition showcases features like pain agnosia due to its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Blastic plasmacytoid dendritic cell neoplasm is a type of acute leukemia that is derived from the precursors of plasmacytoid dendritic cells. This neoplasm is characterized by a high frequency of cutaneous and bone marrow involvement and leukemic dissemination. The most common symptom of BPDCN is skin lesions appearing on the arms, legs, face, and neck. Additionally, other symptoms include low counts of healthy blood cells and swollen lymph nodes, which are indicative of some form of lymphadenopathy. Moreover, blastic plasmacytoid dendritic cell neoplasm is also associated with skin lesions as a symptom.

Blastic plasmacytoid dendritic cell neoplasm is known by various exact synonyms, including Agranular CD4+ CD56+ Hematodermic Neoplasm/Tumor, Agranular CD4+ Natural Killer Cell Leukemia, Blastic NK-Cell Lymphoma, Blastic Natural Killer Leukemia/Lymphoma, CD4+/CD56+ Hematodermic Neoplasm, and natural killer (NK) cell leukemia/lymphoma.

Ectodermal Dysplasia and Immune Deficiency is a condition that falls into several categories: it is a type of Ectodermal Dysplasia, a type of Primary Immunodeficiency Disease, and a type of condition that has at least a phenotype featuring some abnormality of immune system physiology. It is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia syndrome characterized by signs of ectodermal dysplasia such as sparse hair, abnormal or missing teeth, decreased or absent sudation, typical facial features including a protruding forehead, wrinkles under the eyes, characteristic periorbital hyperpigmentation, and immunodeficiency. Additionally, Ectodermal Dysplasia and Immune Deficiency is exactly synonymous with Anhidrotic Ectodermal Dysplasia with Immune Deficiency and Ectodermal Dysplasia, Hypohidrotic, with Immune Deficiency.

Ectodermal Dysplasia and Immunodeficiency 1 is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a form of ectodermal dysplasia and immune deficiency. It is associated with a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and exhibits a phenotype characterized by abnormalities of immune system physiology. The condition is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia and immunodeficiency characterized by the onset of recurrent severe infections due to immunodeficiency in early infancy or in the first years of life, with its material basis in a hemizygous mutation in the IKK-gamma gene (IKBKG) on chromosome Xq28.

Ectodermal dysplasia and immunodeficiency 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of ectodermal dysplasia and immune deficiency. It is characterized by variable features of ectodermal dysplasia, such as hypo/anhidrosis, sparse hair, tooth anomalies, and various immunologic and infectious phenotypes of differing severity. This condition has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NFKBIA gene on chromosome 14q13 and is associated with abnormalities of immune system physiology.

Acute myeloid leukemia with t(6;9)(p23;q34.1) is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. It is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia associated with t(6;9)(p23;q34), which results in DEK-NUP214(CAN) fusion protein expression and is often associated with multilineage dysplasia and basophilia. This condition is exactly synonymous with "Acute Myeloid Leukemia with t(6;9) (p23;q34.1); DEK-NUP214," "DEK-NUP214," and "acute myeloid leukemia with t(6;9)(p23;q34)."

Acute promyelocytic leukemia with PML RARA is a specific type of acute promyelocytic leukemia. It is defined as an acute promyelocytic leukemia that is characterized by severe coagulopathy and the presence of the t(15;17)(q24;q21) genetic abnormality, which generates a PML-RARA fusion gene, and is distinguished by a predominance of abnormal promyelocytes. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with acute promyelocytic leukemia, t(15;17)(q22;q11-12).
Acute myelomonocytic leukemia is a type of acute myeloid leukemia, defined as an acute myeloid leukemia characterized by the proliferation of both neutrophil and monocyte precursors.

Acute myeloid leukemia with inv(3)(q21.3;q26.2) or t(3;3)(q21.3;q26.2) is a specific type of acute myeloid leukemia. This form of leukemia is characterized by the presence of inv(3)(q21q26.2) or t(3;3)(q21;q26.2), which leads to the expression of the RPN1-EVI1 fusion protein and the repositioning of a distal GATA2 enhancer that activates MECOM expression. It is also synonymously known as Acute Myeloid Leukemia with inv(3)(q21.3;q26.2) or t(3;3)(q21.3;q26.2); GATA2, MECOM, and Acute myeloid leukemia with inv(3)(q21;q26.2) or t(3;3)(q21;q26.2); RPN1-EVI1.

Acute myeloid leukemia with inv(16)(p13.1q22) or t(16;16)(p13.1;q22) is a type of acute myeloid leukemia characterized by the presence of abnormal bone marrow eosinophils and the distinctive cytogenetic abnormality of either inv(16)(p13.1q22) or t(16;16)(p13.1;q22). This results in the expression of the fusion protein CBFB-MYH11. It is exactly synonymized as Acute Myeloid Leukemia with inv(16)(p13.1q22) or t(16;16)(p13.1;q22); CBFB-MYH11 and also as acute myeloid leukemia with abnormal marrow eosinophils.

Acute myeloid leukemia with minimal differentiation is a type of acute myeloid leukemia characterized by an absence of evidence for myeloid differentiation in the blasts, as determined through morphology and conventional cytochemistry. It is exactly synonymous with AML-M0 and Acute myeloid leukemia, minimal differentiation.

Acute myeloid leukemia without maturation is a type of acute myeloid leukemia that is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia characterized by blasts without evidence of significant maturation in the neutrophilic lineage.

Acute myeloid leukemia with maturation is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. It is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia characterized by blasts with evidence of significant maturation in the neutrophilic lineage.

Chronic myelogenous leukemia BCR ABL1 positive is a type of chronic myeloid leukemia that is characterized by an abnormally high number of neutrophils and the expression of the BCR-ABL1 fusion gene. It also has the exact synonym "Chronic myelogenous leukemia, BCR/ABL positive."

Acute myeloid leukemia with mutated NPM1 is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. It is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia with mutation of the nucleophosmin gene, usually associated with a normal karyotype, and frequently has myelomonocytic or monocytic features.
Acute myeloid leukemia with biallelic mutation of CEBPA is a type of acute myeloid leukemia, defined as an acute myeloid leukemia with double mutations of the CEBPA gene.

Acute myeloid leukemia with mutated RUNX1 is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. It is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia that is characterized by a de novo RUNX1 gene mutation, not associated with myelodysplastic syndrome-related cytogenetic abnormalities.

Acute myeloid leukemia with myelodysplasia-related changes is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. This specific leukemia is defined by having at least 20% blasts in the bone marrow or blood and one of the following criteria: a previous history of myelodysplastic syndrome, multilineage dysplasia, or myelodysplastic syndrome-related cytogenetic abnormalities.

Acute myeloid leukemia with t(8;21)(q22;q22.1) is a type of acute myeloid leukemia. It is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia associated with t(8;21)(q22;q22) that results in RUNX1-RUNX1T1 fusion protein expression. This condition is characterized by the presence of large myeloblasts with abundant basophilic cytoplasm, often containing azurophilic granules, in both the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. It has exact synonyms including Acute Myeloid Leukemia with t(8;21); (q22; q22.1); RUNX1-RUNX1T1 and acute myeloid leukemia, t(8;21)(q22;q22).

Acute myeloid leukemia with MLL rearrangement is a type of acute myeloid leukemia that is characterized by the rearrangement of the MLL (mixed-lineage leukemia) gene. It is also exactly synonymous with Acute Myeloid Leukemia with KMT2A/MLL Rearrangement and acute myeloid leukemia, 11q23 abnormalities.
Acute myeloid leukemia with mutated CEBPA is a type of acute myeloid leukemia, defined as an acute myeloid leukemia with non-germline mutations of the CEBPA gene.

Acute myeloid leukemia with t(1;22)(p13;q13) is a type of acute myeloid leukemia, which is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia typically showing megakaryocytic maturation and is associated with t(1;22)(p13;q13), resulting in the expression of the RBM15-MKL1 fusion protein. It also has the exact synonym "Acute Myeloid Leukemia (Megakaryoblastic) with t(1;22)(p13.3;q13.1); RBM15-MKL1."

Rafiq syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder characterized by variably impaired intellectual and motor development, a characteristic facial dysmorphism, truncal obesity, and hypotonia. It is caused by a homozygous mutation in the MAN1B1 gene on chromosome 9q34. Rafiq syndrome is also exactly referred to as MENTAL RETARDATION, AUTOSOMAL RECESSIVE 15.

Autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder 13 is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the TRAPPC9 gene on chromosome 8q24.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with brain abnormalities, poor growth, and dysmorphic facies is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder, also known as autosomal recessive mental retardation 36. This condition is defined by a global developmental delay with delayed walking, impaired intellectual development, and speech delay apparent from infancy or early childhood. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the ADAT3 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Spastic paraplegia with deafness is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia, an X-linked recessive disease, and it falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance and whose existence starts during childhood onset. It is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by spastic paraplegia, tremor, cataracts, deafness, short stature, and hypogonadism, presenting at the end of the first decade of life. Moreover, spastic paraplegia with deafness is exactly synonymous with Spastic paraparesis-deafness syndrome and Wells Jankovic Syndrome.

Nonautoimmune hyperthyroidism is a type of hyperthyroidism and an autosomal dominant disease; it is also a condition that, at a minimum, has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as hyperthyroidism characterized by the passive transfer of maternal autoantibodies, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor gene (TSHR) on chromosome 14q31. Additionally, nonautoimmune hyperthyroidism is exactly synonymous with Congenital nonautoimmune hyperthyroidism.

Familial gestational hyperthyroidism is a type of hyperthyroidism that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It is also recognized as a condition that fundamentally involves some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Familial gestational hyperthyroidism is defined by its characteristic promiscuous stimulation of the thyrotropin receptor due to excess chorionic gonadotropin. This condition is rooted in a heterozygous mutation in the gene that encodes the thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR) located on chromosome 14q31.

Hot water epilepsy is a type of reflex epilepsy, which is characterized by seizures triggered by the stimulus of bathing with hot water poured over the head. It is also known as bathing epilepsy and water immersion epilepsy.

Keratosis palmoplantaris striata is a type of palmoplantar keratosis, which is defined as a palmoplantar keratosis characterized by hyperkeratotic lesions. These lesions are restricted to the pressure regions and extend longitudinally along the length of each finger to the palm.

Hot Water Epilepsy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of hot water epilepsy, characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a hot water epilepsy that has its material basis in a susceptibility locus for hot water epilepsy (HWE1) mapped to chromosome 10q21.3-q22.3. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with Hot Water Epilepsy, 1.
Hot Water Epilepsy 2 is a type of Hot Water Epilepsy that is characterized by a material basis linked to chromosome 4q24-q28. It is also precisely known as Hot Water Epilepsy, 2.

Keratosis palmoplantaris striata 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of keratosis palmoplantaris striata, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a keratosis palmoplantaris striata characterized by hyperkeratotic lesions that are restricted to the pressure regions, extending longitudinally along the length of each finger to the palm. This particular condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DSG1 gene located on chromosome 18q12.

Keratosis palmoplantaris striata 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it also falls under the broader category of keratosis palmoplantaris striata. This specific condition is defined by a type of keratosis palmoplantaris striata characterized by linear hyperkeratosis of the palms, which becomes particularly evident in affected individuals who perform manual labor. Its material basis is linked to autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the DSP gene located on chromosome 6p24.

Keratosis palmoplantaris striata 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which falls under the broader category of keratosis palmoplantaris striata. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a keratosis palmoplantaris striata that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the keratin-1 gene (KRT1) located on chromosome 12q13.

Osteosclerotic metaphyseal dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of metaphyseal dysplasia, which is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a metaphyseal dysplasia characterized by distinctive radiographic changes, including osteosclerosis localized predominantly to the metaphyses of the long bones, and has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the LRRK1 gene on chromosome 15q26.

Baraitser Winter Syndrome 1 is a type of Baraitser Winter Syndrome and falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. It specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined by a Baraitser-Winter syndrome that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the ACTB gene on chromosome 7p22. Additionally, a subset of patients exhibit a larger deletion of chromosome 7p22 that includes the ACTB gene and other variable genes, which aligns with a contiguous gene deletion syndrome.

Baraitser Winter Syndrome 2 is a type of Baraitser Winter Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which means it is a condition that at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, Baraitser Winter Syndrome 2 is defined as a Baraitser-Winter syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ACTG1 gene located on chromosome 17q25.

Benign Familial Infantile Seizures 1 (BFIS1) is recognized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also categorized under benign familial infantile epilepsy. This condition is noted for its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. BFIS1 is defined as a benign familial infantile epilepsy characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures that occur between 3 and 12 months of age. Patients typically respond well to medication, and there are no neurologic sequelae associated with this condition. The genetic basis for BFIS1 is located at the BFIS1 locus on chromosome 19q. Additionally, BFIS1 is exactly synonymous with Benign Familial Infantile Seizures, 1.

Benign Familial Infantile Seizures 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, benign familial infantile epilepsy, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a benign familial infantile epilepsy characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures occurring between 3 and 12 months of age with a good response to medication and no neurologic sequelae. This condition has its material basis in mutation in the PRRT2 gene on chromosome 16p11. Moreover, it has the exact synonym Benign Familial Infantile Seizures, 2.

Benign Familial Infantile Seizures 3 is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal dominant disease, a benign familial infantile epilepsy, and it is characterized by having at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific condition is defined as a benign familial infantile epilepsy characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures occurring between 3 and 12 months of age, with patients typically responding well to medication and experiencing no neurologic sequelae. The condition has its material basis in mutations in the SCN2A gene located on chromosome 2q24. Additionally, Benign Familial Infantile Seizures 3 is also known by two exact synonyms: "Benign Familial Infantile Seizures, 3" and "benign familial neonatal-infantile seizures."

Benign familial infantile seizures 4 is a type of benign familial infantile epilepsy, which is defined as a benign familial infantile epilepsy characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures occurring between 3 and 12 months of age. It has a good response to medication and no neurologic sequelae, with its material basis associated with chromosome 1p36.12-p35.1. Moreover, it has an exact synonym, Benign Familial Infantile Seizures, 4.

Benign familial infantile seizures 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of benign familial infantile epilepsy, which essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a benign familial infantile epilepsy characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures occurring between 3 and 12 months of age. These seizures have a good response to medication, result in no neurologic sequelae, and are due to a mutation in the SCN8A gene on chromosome 12q13. Additionally, it has the exact synonym, Benign Familial Infantile Seizures, 5.

Benign familial infantile seizures 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, benign familial infantile epilepsy, and something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a benign familial infantile epilepsy characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures occurring between 3 and 12 months of age, with a good response to medication and no neurologic sequelae. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the CHRNA2 gene on chromosome 8p21. Furthermore, benign familial infantile seizures 6 is also known by its exact synonyms: Autosomal dominant nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy, Benign Familial Infantile Seizures, 6, and nocturnal frontal lobe epilepsy-4.

Graves ophthalmopathy is a type of autoimmune disease of the eyes, ear, nose, and throat, characterized by upper eyelid retraction, lid lag, swelling, redness, conjunctivitis, and bulging eyes. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Graves orbitopathy, Thyroid associated ophthalmopathy, and thyroid eye disease.

Inclusion Body Myopathy and Brain White Matter Abnormalities is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is also known as a type of Inclusion Body Myopathy with Paget Disease of Bone and Frontotemporal Dementia. This condition is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and typically starts during adult onset. It is defined as an Inclusion Body Myopathy with Paget Disease of Bone and Frontotemporal Dementia characterized by proximal limb girdle muscle weakness affecting the lower and upper limbs, leading to gait difficulties and scapular winging. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ANXA11 gene on chromosome 10q22. Moreover, Inclusion Body Myopathy and Brain White Matter Abnormalities has the exact synonym Multisystem Proteinopathy 6.

Catel Manzke syndrome is a type of bone disease characterized by the Pierre Robin anomaly, which includes cleft palate, glossoptosis, and micrognathia, alongside a unique form of bilateral hyperphalangy where there is an accessory bone inserted between the second metacarpal and its corresponding proximal phalanx. This condition results in radial deviation of the index finger and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TGDS gene on chromosome 13q32. Additionally, Catel Manzke syndrome is also known by the exact synonyms Hyperphalangy-clinodactyly of index finger with Pierre Robin syndrome and Micrognathia digital syndrome.

X-linked mental retardation Gustavson type is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance and its existence starts during infantile onset. This condition is defined as a syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by severe intellectual disability, microcephaly, post-natal growth retardation, severe visual impairment or blindness, severe hearing defect, spasticity, epileptic seizures, restricted large-joint movements, and early death. Additionally, X-linked mental retardation Gustavson type has the exact synonym "mental retardation with optic atrophy, deafness, and seizures."

Craniofacial dysmorphism skeletal anomalies and impaired intellectual development syndrome 1 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also recognized as a type of craniofacial dysmorphism skeletal anomalies and mental retardation syndrome. This condition is part of a category that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a specific set of characteristics, including craniofacial dysmorphism, skeletal anomalies, and mental retardation syndrome, notable for cranial involvement that presents with macrocrania at birth, brachycephaly, and anomalies of middle fossa structures. This includes hypoplasia of the corpus callosum, enlargement of the septum pellucidum, dilated lateral ventricles, alongside cortical atrophy and hypodensity of the gray matter. The syndrome's material basis is linked to a homozygous mutation in the TMCO1 gene located on chromosome 1q24.

Craniofacial dysmorphism skeletal anomalies and impaired intellectual development syndrome 2 is a subtype of craniofacial dysmorphism skeletal anomalies and mental retardation syndrome. It is defined as a syndrome featuring craniofacial dysmorphism, skeletal anomalies, and mental retardation, characterized by a flat face, low-set ears, and cleft lip and palate, in addition to costovertebral anomalies such as bifid and fused ribs, vertebral segmentation defects, and scoliosis. The intellectual delay observed in this syndrome can be severe, including absent speech. The syndrome has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the RAB5IF gene located on chromosome 20q11.

De Santo-Shinawi Syndrome is an autosomal dominant disease that is also recognized as a syndrome with its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition starts affecting individuals during infancy or childhood. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by global developmental delay apparent in infancy or early childhood, associated with distinctive dysmorphic facial features such as a broad forehead, depressed nasal bridge with a bulbous nasal tip, and deep-set eyes. The syndrome has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the WAC gene on chromosome 10p11 or deletion at chromosome 10p12-p11. De Santo-Shinawi Syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including Chromosome 10p12-p11 Deletion Syndrome, Facial Dysmorphism-Developmental Delay-Behavioral Abnormalities Syndrome due to 10p11.21p12.31 microdeletion, Facial Dysmorphism-Developmental Delay-Behavioral Abnormalities Syndrome due to WAC point mutation, and WAC-related Facial Dysmorphism-Developmental Delay-Behavioral Abnormalities Syndrome.

Mandibuloacral dysplasia is a type of bone development disease that is defined by underdevelopment of the lower jaw and the collarbone, bone loss at the ends of the fingers and toes, skin degeneration, and partial lipodystrophy, which is characterized by a selective loss of body fat from various parts of the body.

Mandibuloacral dysplasia type A lipodystrophy is a type of mandibuloacral dysplasia, defined by a mandibuloacral dysplasia that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding lamin A/C (LMNA) on chromosome 1q22. This condition is characterized by growth retardation, craniofacial anomalies including mandibular hypoplasia, skeletal abnormalities with progressive osteolysis of the distal phalanges and clavicles, and pigmentary skin changes. Additionally, the lipodystrophy aspect is highlighted by a significant acral loss of fatty tissue, while normal or increased fatty tissue is observed in the neck and trunk.

Mandibuloacral dysplasia type B lipodystrophy is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the broader category of mandibuloacral dysplasia. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by a compound heterozygous mutation in the ZMPSTE24 gene on chromosome 1p34. It is marked by postnatal growth retardation, craniofacial anomalies such as mandibular hypoplasia, skeletal anomalies including progressive osteolysis of the terminal phalanges and clavicles, and skin changes like mottled hyperpigmentation and atrophy. Additionally, the lipodystrophy associated with this condition is characterized by a generalized loss of subcutaneous fat, affecting the face, trunk, and extremities.

BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia C is a type of autosomal recessive disease, tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4) deficient hyperphenylalaninemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by hyperphenylalaninemia, depletion of the neurotransmitters dopamine and serotonin, and progressive cognitive and motor deficits. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the QDPR gene, which encodes an enzyme involved in the salvage pathway for BH4, on chromosome 4p15. Moreover, BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia C is also known by its exact synonym, tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia due to dihydropteridine reductase deficiency.

BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia D is a type of autosomal recessive disease, tetrahydrobiopterin BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia characterized by mild transient hyperphenylalaninemia often detected by newborn screening and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PCBD gene, which encodes an enzyme involved in the salvage pathway for BH4, on chromosome 10q22. Additionally, BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia D has an exact synonym: tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)-deficient hyperphenylalaninemia (HPA) due to pterin-4-alpha-carbinolamine dehydratase deficiency.

Tetrahydrobiopterin BH4 deficient hyperphenylalaninemia is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder, defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized phenotypically by hyperphenylalaninemia, depletion of the neurotransmitters dopamine and serotonin, and progressive cognitive and motor deficits. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive mutations in the genes encoding enzymes involved in the synthesis or regeneration of BH4.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 7a is an autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria characterized by cataracts, neurologic involvement, and neutropenia. It fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria primarily characterized by increased levels of 3-methylglutaconic acid (3-MGA) associated with variable neurologic deficits and neutropenia, which results from a heterozygous dominant-negative mutation in the CLPB gene located on chromosome 11q13.

3 Methylglutaconic aciduria type 7b is a type of 3 methylglutaconic aciduria characterized by cataracts, neurologic involvement, and neutropenia. It is also a type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, 3 methylglutaconic aciduria type 7b is defined as a 3-methylglutaconic aciduria that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous loss-of-function mutations in the CLPB gene on chromosome 11q13.

Agammaglobulinemia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of agammaglobulinemia, indicating that it is something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an agammaglobulinemia that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the immunoglobulin lambda-like-1 gene (IGLL1) on chromosome 22q11.

Agammaglobulinemia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of agammaglobulinemia. It is characterized as something that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, agammaglobulinemia 1 is defined as an agammaglobulinemia that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the mu heavy-chain gene (IGHM) located on chromosome 14q32.

Agammaglobulinemia 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of agammaglobulinemia. It is categorized under conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an agammaglobulinemia that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CD79A gene located on chromosome 19q13.2.

Agammaglobulinemia 6 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is a category of agammaglobulinemia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, agammaglobulinemia 6 is defined by an agammaglobulinemia that results from a homozygous mutation in the CD79B gene located on chromosome 17q23.

Agammaglobulinemia 7 is a type of agammaglobulinemia and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, agammaglobulinemia 7 is defined as an agammaglobulinemia that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PIK3R1 gene located on chromosome 5q13.

Agammaglobulinemia 8a is a type of agammaglobulinemia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a type that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Moreover, agammaglobulinemia 8a is defined as an agammaglobulinemia that results from a heterozygous dominant-negative mutation in the TCF3 gene on chromosome 19p13.
