Agammaglobulinemia 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a form of agammaglobulinemia. It is characterized by recurrent bacterial infections associated with agammaglobulinemia and the absence of circulating B cells. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC39A7 gene located on chromosome 6p21. Moreover, agammaglobulinemia 9 is a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Agammaglobulinemia 10 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of agammaglobulinemia. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and typically begins during childhood. The disease is defined as an agammaglobulinemia characterized by early-childhood onset of recurrent viral and bacterial infections affecting various organ systems, particularly the sinopulmonary system, and is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SPI1 gene on chromosome 11p11.

Agammaglobulinemia 8b is a type of agammaglobulinemia and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and those whose existence starts during childhood onset. It is defined as an agammaglobulinemia characterized by the onset of recurrent infections in early childhood, with this condition having a material basis in homozygous loss-of-function mutation in the TCF3 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Common variable immunodeficiency 1 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency and it is also a type of condition that has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is defined as a common variable immunodeficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ICOS gene located on chromosome 2q33.

Common Variable Immunodeficiency 2 (CVID 2) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the broader category of common variable immunodeficiency. It is characterized by having a material basis in either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, CVID 2 is defined by a common variable immunodeficiency that arises from heterozygous, homozygous, or compound heterozygous mutations in the TNFRSF13B gene. This gene is responsible for encoding the transmembrane activator and CAML interactor (TACI), located on chromosome 17p11.2.

Common variable immunodeficiency 3 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency and is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a common variable immunodeficiency that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CD19 gene on chromosome 16p11.2.

Common variable immunodeficiency 4 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a common variable immunodeficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the BAFFR gene (TNFRSF13C), which encodes the B-cell activating factor receptor, on chromosome 22q13.

Common Variable Immunodeficiency 5 is a type of Common Variable Immunodeficiency and is also characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Common Variable Immunodeficiency that results from a homozygous mutation in the CD20 gene (MS4A1) located on chromosome 11q13.

Common variable immunodeficiency 6 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a common variable immunodeficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CD81 gene on chromosome 11p.

Common variable immunodeficiency 7 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency and is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Common Variable Immunodeficiency 8 (CVID8) is a type of Common Variable Immunodeficiency and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Common Variable Immunodeficiency 10 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of Common Variable Immunodeficiency, which is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Common variable immunodeficiency 11 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency, and it is defined by a common variable immunodeficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the IL21 gene located on chromosome 4q27.

Common variable immunodeficiency 12 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency that is characterized by recurrent infections and associated with hypogammaglobulinemia. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NFKB1 gene on chromosome 4q24.

Common variable immunodeficiency 13 is a type of common variable immunodeficiency and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a common variable immunodeficiency that is characterized by recurrent bacterial infections, mainly affecting the respiratory tract, and associated with hypogammaglobulinemia and decreased numbers of B cells. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the IKZF1 gene on chromosome 7p12.

Common variable immunodeficiency 14 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of common variable immunodeficiency, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Dilated cardiomyopathy 1ll is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific type of dilated cardiomyopathy. Dilated cardiomyopathy 1mm is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a kind of dilated cardiomyopathy. Specifically, this form of dilated cardiomyopathy is defined as a condition that results from a heterozygous mutation in the MYBPC3 gene located on chromosome 11p11.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 2c is a type of dilated cardiomyopathy and an autosomal recessive disease that generally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by dilated cardiomyopathy of variable severity, with the age of onset ranging from 2 to 20 years, and it has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PPCS gene on chromosome 1p34.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 2d is a type of dilated cardiomyopathy and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a dilated cardiomyopathy with neonatal onset of severe cardiomyopathy, leading to rapid progression to cardiac decompensation and death unless treated with heart transplantation. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RPL3L gene on chromosome 16p13.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 2e is a type of dilated cardiomyopathy and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a dilated cardiomyopathy characterized by neonatal or early childhood onset, with rapid progression to cardiac failure and death unless patients undergo cardiac transplantation. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the JPH2 gene on chromosome 20q13.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 2f is a type of dilated cardiomyopathy and an autosomal recessive disease which is characterized by refractory ventricular arrhythmias and severe heart failure. This condition has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and specifically, it has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the BAG5 gene on chromosome 14q32.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 2G is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a type of dilated cardiomyopathy that shares at least a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a dilated cardiomyopathy characterized by early-onset severe dilated cardiomyopathy that rapidly progresses to heart failure in the neonatal period without evidence of intervening hypertrophy. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the LMOD2 gene on chromosome 7q31.

Dilated cardiomyopathy 3b is a type of dilated cardiomyopathy and an X-linked monogenic disease, which indicates it is a form of disease that at least has a material basis in X-linked inheritance. HMG CoA synthase 2 deficiency is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease and falls under the category of amino acid metabolic disorders. It is defined by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Clinically, this condition is identified by episodes of decompensation, often triggered by gastroenteritis or fasting, which manifest through symptoms such as vomiting, lethargy, hepatomegaly, non-ketotic hypoglycemia, and, in rare instances, coma. The root cause of HMG CoA synthase 2 deficiency is traced back to a mutation in the HMGCS2 gene located on chromosome 1p12. This disorder is also precisely known as 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA synthase-2 deficiency.
Leber congenital amaurosis 19 is a type of Leber congenital amaurosis, characterized by a mutation in the USP45 gene on chromosome 6q16. Furthermore, it exactly matches OMIM:618513.

Short stature, hearing loss, retinitis pigmentosa, and distinctive facies constitute a syndrome that is an autosomal recessive disease and is defined as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by short stature, brachydactyly, dysmorphic facial features, hearing loss, and visual impairment, which has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the EXOSC2 gene located on chromosome 9q34.

Hypotonia ataxia and delayed development syndrome is a syndrome and a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital hypotonia, delayed psychomotor development, variable intellectual disability with speech delay, variable dysmorphic facial features, and ataxia, often associated with cerebellar hypoplasia. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the EBF3 gene on chromosome 10q26.

Acromesomelic dysplasia 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of acromesomelic dysplasia, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an acromesomelic dysplasia characterized by disproportionate short stature due to mesomelic shortening of the limbs, with its material basis in homozygous mutation in the PRKG2 gene on chromosome 4q21.

Injection anthrax is a type of anthrax disease characterized by infection at the injection site or deep under the skin or in the muscle where the drug was injected, caused by heroin contaminated with anthrax spores. It is also precisely known as injectional anthrax and injectional anthrax syndrome.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which is a category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a peroxisome biogenesis disorder characterized by the overlapping phenotypes of neonatal adrenoleukodystrophy and infantile Refsum disease. Moreover, it has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PEX1 gene located on chromosome 7q21.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 3b is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a peroxisome biogenesis disorder that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX12 gene on chromosome 17.

Autoimmune interstitial lung, joint, and kidney disease is a type of autosomal dominant, autoimmune syndrome characterized by interstitial lung disease, inflammatory arthritis, and immune complex-mediated renal disease. This disease has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COPA gene located on chromosome 1q23 and is associated with at least some autosomal dominant inheritance and abnormal immunoglobulin levels. Furthermore, it is known by the exact synonyms "Autoimmune interstitial lung disease-arthritis syndrome" and "COPA syndrome."

Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata type 4 is a type of rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata, defined by a rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FAR1 gene on chromosome 11p15. This mutation, required for the conversion of fatty acyl-CoAs to fatty alcohols, leads to a reduction or complete loss of FAR1 activity, resulting in peroxisomal FAR1 deficiency.

Pituitary blastoma is a type of blastoma, pituitary cancer, and something that at least derives from some non terminally differentiated cell. It is defined as a pituitary cancer characterized by features of Cushing disease, with elevated blood ACTH levels and hypercortisolism arising within the fetal anterior pituitary and associated with DICER1 mutations. Additionally, it has the exact synonym Pituitary Gland Blastoma.

A cauda equina neuroendocrine tumor is a type of cauda equina neoplasm characterized by being a slow-growing, well-differentiated neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the cauda equina. It is also exactly synonymous with "Cauda equina neuroendocrine tumour" and "Spinal neuroendocrine tumors."
A teratoma with somatic type malignancy is a type of teratoma that is defined by a teratoma characterized by morphologic transformation to malignancy and an aggressive clinical course.

Dedifferentiated chondrosarcoma is a type of chondrosarcoma defined as an aggressive morphologic variant of chondrosarcoma. It is composed of a low-grade chondrosarcoma and a high-grade non-cartilaginous sarcomatous component.

Pineocytoma is a type of endocrine organ benign neoplasm and is also a type of disease that has its location in the pineal body. It has an exact synonym of Pinealocytoma and is also known as Pinealoma. Pineocytoma is defined as an endocrine organ benign neoplasm arising from the pineal gland. This neoplasm is composed of small, uniform, mature cells resembling pineocytes with occasional large pineocytomatous rosettes. It may exhibit a wide range of divergent phenotypes, including neuronal, glial, melanocytic, photoreceptor, and mesenchymal differentiation.

EWSR1 negative small round cell tumor is a type of small cell sarcoma characterized by the absence of EWSR1 rearrangement and the presence of small round malignant cells with a small amount of cytoplasm. It also has the exact synonym EWSR1-Negative Small Blue Round Cell Tumor.

CIC rearranged sarcoma is a type of EWSR1 negative small round cell tumor that is characterized by a recurrent translocation involving the CIC gene on chromosome 19 and either the DUX4 gene on chromosome 4 or the DUX4L gene on chromosome 10. This translocation results in either CIC-DUX4, t(4;19)(q35;q13) or CIC-DUX4L, t(10;19)(q26;q13) fusions. Furthermore, CIC rearranged sarcoma is also known by its exact synonym, Capicua transcriptional repressor (CIC)-rearranged sarcoma.

Papillary tumor of the pineal region is a type of pineal gland cancer, which is defined as a pineal gland cancer characterized by the presence of neuroepithelial cells and a papillary architecture. It is also exactly synonymous with Papillary tumour of the pineal region.
Supratentorial ependymoma ZFTA fusion positive is a type of supratentorial ependymoma, which is characterized by the presence of a fusion gene involving the ZFTA gene.
Supratentorial ependymoma YAP1 fusion positive is a type of supratentorial ependymoma that is defined by the characteristic presence of a fusion gene involving the YAP1 gene.

Posterior fossa group A ependymoma is a specific type of posterior fossa ependymoma characterized by its origin in the posterior fossa and distinct DNA methylation patterns, including CpG island hypermethylation, global DNA hypomethylation, a reduction of nuclear H3 p.K28me3 (K27me3) expression, and EZHIP overexpression. It is exactly synonymous with both Posterior Fossa Ependymoma, Group A (PFA) and Posterior fossa group A (PFA) ependymoma.

Posterior fossa group B ependymoma is a type of posterior fossa ependymoma that is characterized by its unique DNA methylation patterns. These patterns include the retention of nuclear H3 p.K28me3 (K27me3) expression, the absence of CpG island hypermethylation, the absence of global DNA hypomethylation, and the absence of EZHIP overexpression. This specific type of ependymoma is also known by its exact synonyms, which are Posterior Fossa Ependymoma, Group B (PFB), and Posterior fossa group B (PFB) ependymoma.

Astrocytoma IDH mutant grade 2 is a type of IDH mutant anaplastic astrocytoma, which is defined as an IDH-mutant anaplastic astrocytoma characterized by the presence of well-differentiated fibrillary glial cells diffusely infiltrating the central nervous system.

Astrocytoma IDH mutant grade 3 is a type of IDH mutant anaplastic astrocytoma, which is defined as an IDH-mutant anaplastic astrocytoma characterized by the presence of increased mitotic activity and anaplastic features.

Desmoplastic Infantile Ganglioglioma/Desmoplastic Infantile Astrocytoma (DIG/DIA) is a type of ganglioglioma and also falls under the category of conditions that typically begin during infancy. It is defined as a ganglioglioma that occurs predominantly in the cerebral hemispheres of infants. These are driven by MAPK pathway activation and are characterized by a mixed astrocytic and neuronal component (DIG) or an astrocytic component only (DIA), embedded in an extensive desmoplastic stroma. They often contain foci of undifferentiated embryonal-like tumour cells. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms such as Desmoplastic Infantile Astrocytoma and Desmoplastic Infantile Ganglioglioma, including the combined term "Desmoplastic Infantile Ganglioglioma and Desmoplastic Infantile Astrocytoma."

Diffuse low-grade glioma with an altered MAPK pathway is a type of low-grade glioma characterized by a gene alteration leading to an abnormality in the MAPK pathway, along with morphological features of astrocytoma or oligodendroglioma.
Angiocentric glioma is a type of low-grade glioma, which is defined as a low-grade glioma characterized by an angiocentric pattern, monomorphic cellular infiltrate, and ependymal differentiation.

Intellectual developmental disorder with hypotonia, impaired speech, and dysmorphic facies is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development and poor or absent speech, hypotonia, ophthalmologic abnormalities, and nonspecific dysmorphic features. This disorder has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TNPO2 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with microcephaly, cataracts, and renal abnormalities is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder and has the exact synonym NEDMCR syndrome. It is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder characterized by global developmental delay, microcephaly, cataracts, and renal abnormalities. This disorder has its material basis in homozygous mutation of the GEMIN4 gene on chromosome 17p13.

Developmental delay, hypotrophy, and dysmorphic features without Moebius syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by developmental delay, hypotrophy, and dysmorphic features. It has a material basis in a homozygous ultra-rare REV3L variant (T2753R).

Intellectual Developmental Disorder with Abnormal Behavior, Microcephaly, and Short Stature is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder that is defined by its characteristics of abnormal behavior, microcephaly, and short stature. This disorder has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PUS7 gene on chromosome 7q22. It is also exactly synonymous with IDDBAS.

Pachygyria microcephaly developmental delay and dysmorphic facies with or without seizures, which has the exact synonym PAMDDFS, is a type of lissencephaly. It is characterized by progressive microcephaly associated with abnormal facial features, hypotonia, and variable global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development. Moreover, this condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TUBGCP2 gene on chromosome 10q26.

Graft versus host disease (GvHD) is a type of immune system disease that is characterized by the recognition of the recipient's tissue as foreign by mature donor T cells, which contaminate the allogeneic bone marrow. This results in a severe inflammatory disease characterized by rashes, diarrhea, and liver disease. The material basis for this condition is associated with a variation in the interleukin-10 gene (IL10) on chromosome 1q32.

Pulmonary venoocclusive disease 1 is a type of pulmonary venoocclusive disease and an autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a pulmonary venoocclusive disease that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BMPR2 gene on chromosome 2q33.

Pulmonary Venoocclusive Disease 2 (PVOD2) is categorized as a type of Pulmonary Venoocclusive Disease, an autosomal recessive disease, and is specifically linked to autosomal recessive inheritance, indicating a genetic basis. The disease is defined by its origin from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the EIF2AK4 gene located on chromosome 15q15. Histologically, it is characterized by widespread fibrous intimal proliferation of septal veins and preseptal venules, often accompanied by pulmonary capillary dilatation and proliferation. Additionally, Pulmonary Venoocclusive Disease 2 is exactly synonymous with Familial Pulmonary Capillary Hemangiomatosis.

Smith-McCort dysplasia 1 is a type of Smith-McCort dysplasia and also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Smith-McCort dysplasia characterized by short limbs and a short trunk with a barrel-shaped chest, and it has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DYM gene (607461) on chromosome 18q21.

Smith-McCort dysplasia 2 is a type of Smith-McCort dysplasia and it is also a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Smith-McCort dysplasia characterized by short trunk dwarfism with a barrel-shaped chest, rhizomelic limb shortening. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RAB33B gene on chromosome 4q31.

Sandestig Stefanova syndrome is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease, which has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, loss of function variant, and is based in some gene. Specifically, it is defined as a syndrome characterized by microcephaly, trigonocephaly, congenital cataracts, microphthalmia, facial findings, camptodactyly, periventricular white matter loss, thin corpus callosum, delayed myelination, and poor prognosis. It has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the NUP188 gene on chromosome 9q34.

Siddiqi syndrome, a type of lipid storage disease, is defined as a condition characterized by global developmental delay, early-onset progressive sensorineural hearing impairment, regression of motor skills, dystonia, poor overall growth, and low body mass index. It has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FITM2 gene located on chromosome 20q13.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 14b is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by a specific condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This disorder is clinically identified by mild intellectual disability, congenital cataracts, progressive hearing loss, and polyneuropathy. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX11B gene located on chromosome 1q21.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with eye movement abnormalities and ataxia (NEDEMA) is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by global developmental delay apparent from infancy, which has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FRMD5 gene on chromosome 15q15. Affected individuals exhibit delayed walking with an unsteady gait, variably impaired intellectual development, learning disabilities, and speech difficulties.

Cerebellar atrophy, visual impairment, and psychomotor retardation is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and also includes a phenotype of neurodevelopmental delay. The existence of this condition starts during childhood onset. Specifically, it is a syndrome characterized by cerebellar atrophy, visual impairment, and psychomotor retardation, with its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the EMC1 gene on chromosome 1p36. Additionally, it has the exact synonym CAVIPMR.

Diffuse pediatric type high-grade glioma H3 wildtype and IDH wildtype is a type of high-grade glioma that is characterized by the absence of histone H3, IDH1, and IDH2 mutations. It also has the exact synonym "diffuse paediatric-type high-grade glioma, H3-wildtype and IDH-wildtype."

Infant type hemispheric glioma is a type of malignant astrocytoma that primarily manifests in early childhood. This disease originates in the cerebral hemisphere and is notably characterized by the presence of receptor tyrosine kinase fusions within the NTRK family, ROS1, ALK, or MET genes. Additionally, it is recognized for its onset during infancy, establishing it as a condition with an infantile onset.

Diffuse astrocytoma MYB or MYBL1 altered is a type of diffuse astrocytoma, defined as a diffusely infiltrative astroglial neoplasm composed of monomorphic cells with genetic alterations in MYB or MYBL1.

Pituicytoma is a type of neoplasm located in the posterior pituitary gland, which is also known as the neurohypophysis. It is characterized by a posterior pituitary gland neoplasm that features elongated, spindle-shaped neoplastic glial cells forming storiform patterns or interlacing fascicular arrangements.

Oligodendroglioma IDH mutant and 1p 19q codeleted grade 2 is a type of IDH mutant and 1p 19q codeleted oligodendroglioma. It is defined as an IDH-mutant, and 1p/19q-codeleted oligodendroglioma that is characterized as a well-differentiated tumor lacking anaplastic features, including brisk mitotic activity, microvascular proliferation, and necrosis.

Oligodendroglioma IDH mutant and 1p 19q codeleted grade 3 is a type of IDH mutant and 1p 19q codeleted oligodendroglioma. It is defined as an IDH-mutant, and 1p/19q-codeleted oligodendroglioma that is characterized as grade 3 tumors. These tumors are associated with more rapid growth and appear to have abnormalities on chromosomes 9 or 10, along with unusual amounts of growth factors and proteins, which are thought to contribute to the more rapid growth of these gliomas.

Papillary glioneuronal tumor is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, which is characterized by the presence of astrocytes that line vascular and hyalinized pseudopapillae. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "Papillary glioneuronal tumour."

The Rosette-forming glioneuronal tumor, also known by its exact synonyms RGNT and Rosette-forming glioneuronal tumour, is classified as a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm. It is defined as a central nervous system benign neoplasm that is distinguished by neurocytes forming pseudorosettes and astrocytes containing Rosenthal fibers.

Myxoid glioneuronal tumor is a type of benign neoplasm of the central nervous system. It is defined as a central nervous system benign neoplasm characterized by a dinucleotide mutation at codon 385 of the PDGFR gene. Typically, it occurs in the septum pellucidum but has also been described in the corpus callosum and periventricular white matter of the lateral ventricle. The tumor is composed of oligodendrocyte-like cells in a prominent myxoid stroma. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, Myxoid glioneuronal tumour.

Embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes is a type of central nervous system embryonal tumor, which is defined as a central nervous system embryonal tumor characterized by the presence of multilayered rosette formation and typically the presence of amplification of the C19MC region on chromosome 19 (19q13.42) or, rarely, a DICER1 mutation. It also has the exact synonym "Embryonal tumour with multilayered rosettes."

White sponge nevus 1 is a type of white sponge nevus and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a white sponge nevus that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the keratin-4 gene (KRT4) on chromosome 12q13.

White sponge nevus 2 is a type of white sponge nevus and an autosomal dominant disease, which falls under things that at least have a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a white sponge nevus that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT13 gene on chromosome 17q21.

Antley Bixler syndrome is a type of craniosynostosis and is defined as a craniosynostosis characterized by radiohumeral synostosis present from the perinatal period. It is also exactly synonymous with both Antley Bixler syndrome and Antley and Bixler's syndrome.

Antley Bixler syndrome without disordered steroidogenesis is identified as a subclass of Antley Bixler syndrome, characterized as an autosomal dominant disease. This particular form of Antley Bixler syndrome is fundamentally based on autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined specifically as an Antley-Bixler syndrome that results from a heterozygous mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor gene, FGFR2, located on chromosome 10q26, distinguishing it as an exclusively skeletal form of Antley-Bixler syndrome.

Chronic traumatic encephalopathy is a type of tauopathy that is defined as a tauopathy characterized by an abundance of hyperphosphorylated tau protein in neurons, astrocytes, and cell processes around blood vessels, and is associated with repetitive head impacts or exposure to blast waves.
Traumatic brain injury is a type of brain disease that is defined as a brain disease characterized by brain dysfunction caused by an outside force, usually a violent blow to the head.

Salivary gland mucoepidermoid carcinoma is a type of carcinoma that is specifically classified both as a type of salivary gland carcinoma and a type of mucoepidermoid carcinoma. It is also defined as a condition that arises from an intersection of characteristics, being at least derived from some epithelial cell and having its location in a saliva-secreting gland. Additionally, salivary gland mucoepidermoid carcinoma is defined as a mucoepidermoid carcinoma located in the salivary gland.

Neuronal intranuclear inclusion disease is a type of autosomal dominant and neurodegenerative disease, which is characterized by a wide spectrum of clinical manifestations such as pyramidal and extrapyramidal symptoms, cerebellar ataxia, cognitive decline and dementia, peripheral neuropathy, and autonomic dysfunction. This condition at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and trinucleotide repeat expansion, specifically a heterozygous repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region of the NOTCH2NLC gene on chromosome 1q21.

Essential tremor 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of essential tremor. It is characterized by at least having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, as well as in trinucleotide repeat expansion. More specifically, it is defined as an essential tremor that manifests through adult-onset kinetic and/or postural tremor, typically affecting the upper limbs. This condition has its material basis in heterozygous trinucleotide GGC repeat expansion in the 5-prime untranslated region of the NOTCH2NLC gene located on chromosome 1q21.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy is a type of myopathy that is defined as a myopathy characterized by progressive external ocular, facial, and pharyngeal muscle weakness. This leads to variable degrees of ptosis, ophthalmoparesis, facial muscle atrophy, dysarthria, and dysphagia, as well as distal muscle weakness and atrophy of lower and upper extremities.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of oculopharyngodistal myopathy. It is characterized by certain traits that are at least partly due to its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and trinucleotide repeat expansion. Specifically, it is defined as an oculopharyngodistal myopathy characterized by adult-onset ptosis, external ophthalmoplegia, facial muscle weakness, distal limb muscle weakness and atrophy, and pharyngeal involvement, which leads to dysphagia and dysarthria. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous trinucleotide repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region of the LRP12 gene on chromosome 8q22.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of oculopharyngodistal myopathy. It is associated with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and involves some trinucleotide repeat expansion. The disease is defined as an oculopharyngodistal myopathy characterized by the onset of distal muscle weakness, mainly in the lower limbs, and/or ophthalmoplegia occurring in the second or third decades of life. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous trinucleotide repeat expansion (GGC(n)) in the 5-prime untranslated region (UTR) of the GIPC1 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a specific subtype of oculopharyngodistal myopathy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is also associated with trinucleotide repeat expansion. Specifically, Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 3 is defined as an oculopharyngodistal myopathy that is distinguished by progressive muscle weakness affecting the eyes, face, throat, and distal limbs. This results in difficulties with speech and gait. The disease has its material basis in a heterozygous trinucleotide repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region (UTR) of the NOTCH2NLC gene located on chromosome 1q21.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of oculopharyngodistal myopathy. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance as well as in trinucleotide repeat expansion, specifically a heterozygous trinucleotide repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region (UTR) of the RILPL1 gene on chromosome 12q24. This condition is characterized by progressive ptosis, ophthalmoparesis, facial and masseter weakness, along with muscle weakness of the distal limbs.

Intellectual developmental disorder with ocular anomalies and distinctive facial features is a type of syndromic intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay, mildly impaired intellectual development, ophthalmologic anomalies, microcephaly or relative microcephaly, hearing loss, and characteristic facial features. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MTSS2 gene on chromosome 16q22. It is exactly synonymous with both IDDOF and MTSS2-related neurodevelopmental disorder.

Diffuse leptomeningeal glioneuronal tumor is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, which is defined as a central nervous system benign neoplasm characterized by the presence of clear glial neoplastic cells reminiscent of oligodendroglioma. It also has the exact synonym "Diffuse leptomeningeal glioneuronal tumour."

The multinodular and vacuolating neuronal tumor is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, which typically begins in middle age and is located in the cerebral hemisphere. It is defined as a central nervous system benign neoplasm composed of cells with glial and/or neuronal differentiation, forming multiple nodules with prominent vacuolation, and affecting the cerebral hemispheres.

High grade astrocytoma with piloid features is a type of anaplastic astrocytoma that is defined as an anaplastic astrocytoma characterized by high-grade piloid and/or glioblastoma-like histological features. It may occur anywhere in the central nervous system but most often arises in the posterior fossa.

Polymorphous low grade neuroepithelial tumour of the young is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm characterized by the presence of oligodendroglioma-like components. It may also contain astrocytic components and is associated with seizures and, in many cases, refractory epilepsy. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms, Massively Calcified Low Grade Glioma and Polymorphous low-grade neuroepithelial tumour of the young.

Spindle cell oncocytoma is a type of posterior pituitary gland neoplasm, which is defined as a posterior pituitary benign neoplasm characterized by the presence of spindle cells with eosinophilic, granular cytoplasm forming fascicles.

Lymphomatoid granulomatosis is a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome, defined as a syndrome characterized by the overproduction (proliferation) of white blood cells called lymphocytes. In this condition, the abnormal cells infiltrate and accumulate (form lesions or nodules) within tissues, where the lesions or nodules damage or destroy the blood vessels within these tissues.

Grade I lymphomatoid granulomatosis is a type of lymphomatoid granulomatosis that is characterized by the presence of a polymorphous lymphoid infiltrate without cytologic atypia, where large lymphocytes are absent or rare. Moreover, by in situ hybridization, EBV-positive cells are infrequently seen.

Grade II lymphomatoid granulomatosis is a type of lymphomatoid granulomatosis that is defined as being characterized by the presence of occasional large lymphoid cells or immunoblasts in a polymorphous background. Compared to Grade I lymphomatoid granulomatosis, necrosis is more commonly seen. Additionally, EBV-positive cells are readily observed through in situ hybridization.

Grade III lymphomatoid granulomatosis is a specific type of lymphomatoid granulomatosis. It is defined as a lymphomatoid granulomatosis characterized by the presence of aggregates of neoplastic large B-lymphocytes, usually admixed with pleomorphic and Hodgkin-like cells, in a background of chronic inflammation. Moreover, necrotic changes are present and are usually extensive.
Intravascular large B-cell lymphoma is a type of B-cell lymphoma that is defined by the characteristic presence of lymphoma cells exclusively in the lumina of small vessels, particularly capillaries.

T cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma is the same as something that lies at the intersection of lymphoma and something that at least has a material basis in some T cell. It is a type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Additionally, T cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma is defined as a non-Hodgkin lymphoma of T-cell lineage.
Primary diffuse large B cell lymphoma of the central nervous system is a type of diffuse large B cell lymphoma, defined as a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma arising from the central nervous system.

Extraventricular neurocytoma is a type of cerebral ventricle cancer characterized by the presence of neoplastic uniform, round cells with neuronal differentiation that arises from the brain parenchyma. Unlike central neurocytoma, it does not involve the lateral ventricles.

A central nervous system tumor with BCOR internal tandem duplication is a specific type of central nervous system embryonal tumor. This tumor is defined by its characterization, which includes the presence of uniform oval or spindle-shaped cells with round or oval nuclei, pseudorosette formation, and a heterozygous internal tandem duplication in exon 15 of the BCOR gene. Moreover, it has an exact synonym: CNS tumor with BCOR internal tandem duplication.

Primary intracranial sarcoma DICER1 mutant is a type of brain sarcoma that is defined as a brain sarcoma composed of malignant pleomorphic or spindle neoplastic cells, typically demonstrating myogenic and/or chondroid differentiation. It usually presents with cytoplasmic eosinophilic globules and myxoid stroma formation and is associated with mutations in the DICER1 gene.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 1 is a type of multiple synostoses syndrome and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by multiple joint fusions, usually starting in the hands, conductive deafness, and distinctive facial features such as a broad, tubular-shaped nose and a thin upper vermilion. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NOG gene located on chromosome 17q22.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 2 is a type of multiple synostoses syndrome and also a type of condition that at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a multiple synostoses syndrome characterized by progressive joint fusions of the fingers, wrists, ankles, and cervical spine; it also features characteristic facies, including a broad hemicylindrical nose, and progressive conductive hearing loss. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDF5 gene located on chromosome 20q11.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 3 is a type of multiple synostoses syndrome and also a kind of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a multiple synostoses syndrome characterized by multiple joint fusions, usually starting in the hands, conductive deafness, and distinctive facial features, such as a broad, tubular-shaped nose and a thin upper vermilion. This syndrome has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FGF9 gene on chromosome 13q12.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 4 is a type of multiple synostoses syndrome and is also a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a multiple synostoses syndrome characterized by the fusion of carpal and tarsal bones, in addition to conductive hearing loss. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDF6 gene located on chromosome 8q22.

Contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome 1a is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also identified as a type of contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by the presence of contractures of proximal and distal joints, pterygia involving the neck, axillae, elbows, and/or knees, as well as variable vertebral, carpal, and tarsal fusions, and short stature, which is attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13. Moreover, it is precisely synonymous with Autosomal dominant multiple pterygium syndrome.

Contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome 1b is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, and it also falls under the broader category of contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome. This condition is characterized by contractures of proximal and distal joints, pterygia involving the neck, elbows, fingers, and/or knees, and variable vertebral, carpal, and tarsal fusions. It has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13. Additionally, it is known by its exact synonym, Autosomal recessive multiple pterygium syndrome.

Breast implant illness is a syndrome and a type of breast disease that occurs in the breast. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by symptoms such as fatigue, problems with memory or concentration, joint and muscle pain, hair loss, weight changes, and anxiety/depression.

The neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by poor growth, spastic tetraplegia, and hearing loss is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder that is characterized by poor growth, spastic tetraplegia, and hearing loss. This disorder has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PSMC1 gene located on chromosome 14q32. Furthermore, this condition is exactly synonymous with NEDGTH.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 94 is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of multiple seizure types in the first few years of life, associated with poor prognosis, and has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CHD2 gene on chromosome 15q26.

Oxoglutarate dehydrogenase deficiency is an autosomal recessive disease that belongs to amino acid metabolic disorders. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically starts during infancy. The disorder is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by symptoms such as infantile and pediatric onset of basal ganglia-associated movement disorders, hypotonia, developmental delays, ataxia, and seizures. This condition results from homozygous mutations in the oxoglutarate dehydrogenase gene (OGDH) located on chromosome 7p13. Furthermore, oxoglutarate dehydrogenase deficiency is also known by its exact synonyms, Oxoglutaric aciduria and alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase deficiency.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with regression, abnormal movements, loss of speech, and seizures is a type of neurodegenerative disease and has the exact synonym NEDAMSS. This disease is defined as a neurodegenerative disease characterized by neurodevelopmental regression which becomes apparent between 2 and 10 years of age after normal early development in most patients, although a few had mild early delays. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the IRF2BPL gene on chromosome 14q24.

Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 8 is defined as a type of hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia that is autosomal recessive. It is characterized by protein-related hypoglycemia, persistent mild hyperammonemia, and has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLC25A36 gene on chromosome 3q23. This condition exhibits a phenotype of abnormal blood glucose concentration, indicating that it at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormal blood glucose levels.

Glycogen Storage Disease I (GSD I) is a specific type of Glycogen Storage Disease. It is also identified by several exact synonyms, including Glycogen Storage Disease 1, Deficiency of Glucose-6-Phosphatase, Glycogen Storage Disease Type I, Glycogenosis Type I, Von Gierke Disease, and Von Gierke's Disease. GSD I is characterized by a constellation of symptoms including severe hypoglycemia, hepatomegaly due to glycogen accumulation, growth retardation, delayed puberty, lactic acidemia, hyperlipidemia, hyperuricemia, and a high incidence of hepatic adenomas in adults. The onset of this disease typically occurs in infancy.

Glycogen storage disease Ib is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of glycogen storage disease I. This categorization is due to its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, glycogen storage disease Ib is defined as a variant of glycogen storage disease I that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the G6PT1 gene (SLC37A4), which is responsible for encoding glucose-6-phosphate translocase, located on chromosome 11q23.

Glycogen storage disease Ic is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of glycogen storage disease I, characterized by having its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a glycogen storage disease I variant that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the G6PT1 gene (SLC37A4), which is responsible for encoding glucose-6-phosphate translocase, located on chromosome 11q23. Notably, G6PT1 is also the site of the defect in glycogen storage disease Ib.

Progeroid syndrome, which is a type of syndrome, is defined as a syndrome characterized by the premature onset of age-related pathologies. It is the same as something that intersects with a disease and something that at least has the phenotype of a prematurely aged appearance. Additionally, progeroid syndrome has the exact synonyms progeroid disease and progeroid syndromes.

Wiedemann Rautenstrauch syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive and progeroid syndrome, which is characterized by intrauterine growth retardation, failure to thrive, short stature, a progeroid appearance, hypotonia, and variable mental impairment. This syndrome has its material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the POLR3A gene on chromosome 10q22 and is known to have an onset during the neonatal period. It also has exact synonyms: Neonatal progeroid syndrome and PROGEROID SYNDROME, NEONATAL.

Nestor Guillermo progeria syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and progeroid syndrome, indicating its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is also characterized by its onset during childhood. Specifically, it is a progeroid syndrome characterized by lipoatrophy, osteoporosis, and very severe osteolysis, but without cardiovascular impairment, diabetes mellitus, or hypertriglyceridemia. The profound skeletal abnormalities present in patients significantly affect their quality of life. The syndrome is caused by a homozygous mutation in the BANF1 gene on chromosome 11q13, with the onset occurring after 2 years of age. Additionally, Nestor Guillermo progeria syndrome has an exact synonym: Progeria syndrome, childhood-onset, with osteolysis.

Becker disease is identified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of myotonia congenita, which specifically involves a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by muscle stiffness and the muscle's failure to relax post voluntary contraction, attributing its cause to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene that encodes the skeletal muscle chloride channel-1 (CLCN1) located on chromosome 7q34. Furthermore, Becker disease is precisely matched with OMIM:255700.

Thomsen disease is a type of autosomal dominant disease, myotonia congenita, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a myotonia congenita characterized by muscle stiffness and an inability of the muscle to relax after voluntary contraction, with the material basis being a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding skeletal muscle chloride channel-1 (CLCN1) on chromosome 7q34. Additionally, Thomsen disease has the exact synonyms Congenital myotonia, autosomal dominant form, and Thomsen's disease.

Congenital myopathy is a type of myopathy that is characterized by hypotonia and weakness, usually present from birth. It is a condition that begins during congenital onset, indicating its presence is established at or before birth.

Myofibrillar myopathy 11 is a type of myofibrillar myopathy that is defined as a myofibrillar myopathy characterized by the onset of slowly progressive proximal muscle weakness in the first decade of life. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the UNC45B gene located on chromosome 17q11.

Congenital myopathy 2b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of congenital myopathy, indicating that it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by severe hypotonia, a notable lack of spontaneous movements, and respiratory insufficiency, typically resulting in death during infancy or early childhood. This condition has its material basis in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ACTA1 gene located on chromosome 1q42.

Congenital Myopathy 2C is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a kind of congenital myopathy. It is characterized by a severe congenital weakness that typically results in death from respiratory failure within the first year or so of life. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ACTA1 gene on chromosome 1q42. Such a heterozygous mutation in the ACTA1 gene is also responsible for autosomal dominant typical congenital myopathy-2A (CMYP2A), while a biallelic mutation in the same gene causes autosomal recessive severe infantile congenital myopathy-2B (CMYP2B).

Congenital Myopathy 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and congenital myopathy, which essentially has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by the onset of muscle weakness in infancy, manifesting as neonatal hypotonia, delayed motor development, and often distal contractures. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding titin (TTN) on chromosome 2q31. Furthermore, Congenital Myopathy 5 is exactly synonymous with Salih Myopathy and Congenital Myopathy-5 with Cardiomyopathy.

Congenital Myopathy 8 is a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by hypotonia and delayed motor development apparent from infancy or childhood, resulting in difficulties walking or loss of ambulation within the first few decades. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ACTN2 gene on chromosome 1q43. Additionally, a heterozygous mutation in the ACTN2 gene can cause Distal Myopathy-6 (MPD6), which has a later onset and is less severe than Congenital Myopathy 8.

Congenital myopathy 9a is a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease. It's defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by neonatal hypotonia, poor feeding, fractures of the long bones, and respiratory insufficiency, with its material basis in homozygous mutation in the FXR1 gene on chromosome 3q28. Furthermore, congenital myopathy 9a is also classified as something that inherently has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Congenital myopathy 9b is a type of congenital myopathy that also qualifies as an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by neonatal hypotonia, followed by mildly delayed walking in childhood, primarily affecting proximal muscles. This condition is rooted in a material basis of autosomal recessive inheritance. The underlying cause is identified as a homozygous mutation in the FXR1 gene on chromosome 3q28. Additionally, biallelic mutation in the FXR1 gene is responsible for CMYP9A.

Congenital myopathy 10b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of congenital myopathy, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by symptoms such as infantile- or childhood-onset myopathy, areflexia, dysphagia, and respiratory distress, often necessitating nocturnal ventilation. This condition arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MEGF10 gene located on chromosome 5q23. Notably, biallelic mutations in the MEGF10 gene can also result in a more severe form of congenital myopathy, sharing overlapping features with congenital myopathy 10b.

Congenital myopathy 14 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, congenital myopathy, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by onset of severe muscle weakness apparent at birth and sometimes in utero. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MYL1 gene on chromosome 2q32, leading to affected infants having difficulty breathing independently, often requiring mechanical ventilation for variable lengths of time.

Congenital myopathy 15 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and congenital myopathy, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by symptom onset soon after birth. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TNNC2 gene on chromosome 20q13, resulting in affected infants being hypotonic and experiencing severe respiratory insufficiency and feeding problems, sometimes necessitating mechanical ventilation or tube feeding.

Congenital myopathy 16 is a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy that manifests with hypotonia and tremor in infancy, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the MYBPC1 gene on chromosome 12q23. Affected patients may experience mildly delayed walking, an unsteady gait, proximal muscle weakness, and a high-frequency tremor of the limbs.

Congenital myopathy 17 is a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease, which is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by hypotonia and respiratory insufficiency present at birth, associated with a high diaphragmatic dome on imaging. This condition has a material basis in homozygous mutations in the MYOD1 gene on chromosome 11p15. It is also described as a condition with at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Congenital myopathy 18 is a type of congenital myopathy that is characterized by the onset of symptoms of muscle weakness early, including in utero and infancy. It is associated with both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive diseases. Specifically, congenital myopathy 18 has a material basis in either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive inheritance, which can be attributed to compound heterozygous or heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1S gene on chromosome 1q32.

Congenital Myopathy 19 is classified as a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease, indicating it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by its infantile-onset of progressive muscle weakness and atrophy, which is also associated with scoliosis, variably impaired walking, and dysmorphic facial features. This condition is specifically caused by a homozygous mutation in the PAX7 gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Congenital myopathy 20 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and congenital myopathy, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RYR3 gene on chromosome 15q13. This condition shows wide phenotypic variability; some patients present in early childhood with proximal muscle weakness affecting the lower and upper limbs, resulting in difficulties running and climbing, while others present soon after birth with congenital limb or distal contractures.

Congenital myopathy 21 is a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by diaphragmatic weakness and spinal rigidity, which has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the DNAJB4 gene on chromosome 1p31.

Congenital myopathy 22a is a type of congenital myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by the onset of muscle weakness in utero or soon after birth. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCN4A gene located on chromosome 17q23. Notably, biallelic mutation in the SCN4A gene is responsible for causing severe fetal congenital myopathy 22B.

Congenital myopathy 22b is a type of congenital myopathy and is classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, congenital myopathy 22b is defined as a congenital myopathy that is characterized by in utero onset of severe muscle weakness manifesting as fetal akinesia, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCN4A gene on chromosome 17q23.

Spinal Muscular Atrophy Jokela Type is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a specific form of spinal muscular atrophy. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and begins during adulthood. The condition is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy that manifests in adults with muscle cramps and fasciculations affecting both the proximal and distal muscles of the upper and lower limbs. This is due to a heterozygous mutation in the CHCHD10 gene located on chromosome 22q11.

Isolated mitochondrial myopathy is a type of mitochondrial myopathy and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by onset of proximal lower limb weakness and exercise intolerance in the first decade of life. It has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and is specifically caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CHCHD10 gene on chromosome 22q11. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with Autosomal dominant mitochondrial myopathy with exercise intolerance.

Epidermolytic hyperkeratosis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of epidermolytic hyperkeratosis, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an epidermolytic hyperkeratosis characterized in adulthood by warty flexural hyperkeratosis with fewer erosions and blisters. Typically, it presents at birth with erythema and blistering, and its material basis is a heterozygous mutation in the keratin-1 gene (KRT1) on chromosome 12q13.

Epidermolytic hyperkeratosis 2 is a type of epidermolytic hyperkeratosis that is defined by generalized erythema, erosions, scaling, and easily breaking blisters which become less frequent later in life, while hyperkeratosis increases. This condition has a material basis in either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the keratin-10 gene (KRT10) located on chromosome 17q21.

Spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy 2 is a type of spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy and is also a type of something that at least has a material basis in some paternal variant. It is defined as a spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy that has its material basis in the deletion of the ANKRD15 gene (KANK1) inherited on the paternal allele.

Spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy 3, also precisely known as CPSQ3, is classified within the broader category of spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy and is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It specifically refers to a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular form of spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy is defined by its origin in a homozygous mutation in the ADD3 gene located on chromosome 10q24.

Pierpont syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder, which is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by distinctive facial characteristics, especially when smiling, plantar fat pads, and other limb anomalies. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TBL1XR1 gene located on chromosome 3q26. It also has exact synonyms, including Plantar lipomatosis-facial dysmorphism-developmental delay syndrome and Plantar lipomatosis-unusual facies-developmental delay syndrome.

Distal myopathy with rimmed vacuoles is a type of distal myopathy, autosomal dominant disease, and something that has at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and starts its existence during adult onset. It is defined as a distal myopathy characterized by adult onset of muscle weakness affecting the distal upper and lower limbs, potentially resulting in walking difficulties, in addition to proximal weakness of the shoulder girdle muscles. This condition has a material basis due to a heterozygous mutation in the SQSTM1 gene on chromosome 5q35.

Neurodegeneration with ataxia, dystonia, and gaze palsy childhood onset is a type of neurodegenerative disease. It is defined as a neurodegenerative disease that is characterized by the onset of gait ataxia, cognitive decline, and gaze palsy in the first or second decades. Additionally, it has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SQSTM1 gene on chromosome 5q35.

Paget's disease of bone 2 is a type of Paget's disease of bone, and it is classified as an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is specifically defined by a Paget's disease of bone that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TNFRSF11A gene, which encodes RANK, on chromosome 18q21. It is also characterized by its autosomal dominant inheritance and typically begins during childhood. Additionally, Paget's disease of bone 2 is exactly synonymous with Paget disease of bone-2.

Paget's disease of bone 3 is a type of Paget's disease of bone and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a Paget's disease of bone that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SQSTM1 gene on chromosome 5q35. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with Paget disease of bone-3.

Paget's disease of bone 4 is a subtype of Paget's disease of bone, classified as an autosomal dominant disease. It is specifically defined as a Paget's disease of bone that is linked to the 5q31 region, within 12.2 cM between D5S642 and D5S1972. This condition is also characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and is exactly synonymous with Paget disease of bone-4.

Paget's disease of bone 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a variant of Paget's disease of bone. It is characterized by conditions that necessarily have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically begin during juvenile onset. This particular form of Paget's disease is distinguished by short stature, progressive long bone deformities, fractures, vertebral collapse, skull enlargement, and hyperostosis with progressive deafness, all of which are attributed to osteoprotegerin deficiency caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TNFRSF11B gene on chromosome 8q24. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including Familial osteoectasia, Hereditary hyperphosphatasia, Hyperostosis corticalis deformans juvenilis, Juvenile Paget disease, and Paget disease of bone-5.

Paget's disease of bone 6, also known exactly as Paget disease of bone-6, is a specific form of Paget's disease of bone. It is characterized as a type of autosomal dominant disease and particularly pertains to conditions that essentially have their material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This disease is defined by an adult onset of bone pain, associated with polyostotic bone lesions primarily affecting the axial skeleton, and is rooted in a heterozygous mutation in the ZNF687 gene on chromosome 1q21.

Ladd syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by defects in the tear-producing lacrimal system, ear problems, dental abnormalities, and deformities of the fingers. It is also known by its exact synonyms, Lacrimo-auriculo-dento-digital (LADD) syndrome and lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome.

Lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a type of LADD syndrome. It is characterized by conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by a LADD syndrome that primarily affects lacrimal glands and ducts, salivary glands and ducts, ears, teeth, and distal limb segments due to a heterozygous mutation in the tyrosine kinase domain of the FGFR3 gene on chromosome 4p16. Moreover, it has the exact synonym Lacrimo-auriculo-dento-digital syndrome 2.

Lacrimoauriculodentodigital syndrome 3, also known precisely as Lacrimo-auriculo-dento-digital syndrome 3, is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically falling under the category of LADD syndrome. This condition is recognized as a form of illness that inherently has its material basis in certain autosomal dominant inheritance patterns. It is defined as a LADD syndrome defined by a collection of symptoms including aplasia, atresia, or hypoplasia of the lacrimal and salivary systems, cup-shaped ears, hearing loss, alongside dental and digital anomalies. This syndrome's underlying cause is traced back to a heterozygous mutation in the FGF10 gene located on chromosome 5p12.

Disabling pansclerotic morphea is a type of localized scleroderma, and it is also a condition that typically begins in childhood. It is defined as a localized scleroderma characterized by the rapid progression of deep cutaneous fibrosis or pansclerosis that involves the subcutaneous adipose tissue and, occasionally, the fascia, muscles, and bone. Furthermore, disabling pansclerotic morphea is exactly synonymous with disabling pansclerotic morphea of childhood.

Nemaline myopathy 5b is a type of nemaline myopathy and an autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TNNT1 gene on chromosome 19q13. Its existence typically begins during childhood. This condition is defined as a nemaline myopathy that specifically arises from such genetic mutations, highlighting its onset during childhood.

Nemaline myopathy 5c is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of nemaline myopathy. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a nemaline myopathy that arises from autosomal dominant inheritance of either a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TNNT1 gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Cox deficiency benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy is a type of cytochrome c oxidase deficiency disease characterized by localization to tissues of the skeletal muscles. It also has the exact synonym "Isolated cytochrome C oxidase deficiency."

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 24 is a subtype of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and an autosomal dominant disease, indicating that it is also classified as a type of condition that necessarily has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and begins during adult onset. Moreover, it is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis characterized by the adult-onset loss of motor neurons, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NEK1 gene on chromosome 4q33.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 25 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and an autosomal dominant disease, characterized by rapidly progressive muscle weakness leading to death due to respiratory failure. This specific type of ALS is linked to a heterozygous mutation in the KIF5A gene on chromosome 12q13. It is noted that ALS25 often presents with a lower median age at onset, which is 46.5 years, and longer median survival, at 10 years, compared to the general findings in epidemiologic studies where the median age at onset is 62.5 years with a median survival of 20 to 30 months. Additionally, it belongs to a category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 26 is a form of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by the adult onset of upper and lower motor neuron disease, leading to bulbar dysfunction and limb weakness, which stems from a heterozygous mutation in the TIA1 gene on chromosome 2p13. This condition not only follows autosomal dominant inheritance patterns but also typically begins during adulthood.

Juvenile Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Type 27 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence starts during some juvenile onset. Furthermore, it is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis characterized by early childhood-onset lower extremity spasticity manifesting as toe walking and gait abnormalities, followed by progressive lower motor neuron-mediated weakness without sensory signs or symptoms, and it has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SPTLC1 gene on chromosome 9q22.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 28 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a specific genetic basis involving an autosomal dominant inheritance and a trinucleotide repeat expansion. Moreover, its existence typically begins in adulthood. Specifically, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 28 is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis characterized by adult onset of slowly progressive limb muscle weakness and atrophy, leading to gait difficulties, loss of ambulation, and distal upper limb weakness. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous trinucleotide repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region of the LRP12 gene on chromosome 8q22.

Ataxia oculomotor apraxia type 4 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the onset of dystonia and ataxia in the first decade. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PNKP gene on chromosome 19q13.

Ataxia telangiectasia like disorder 1 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that is clinically characterized by progressive cerebellar degeneration leading to ataxia and oculomotor apraxia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MRE11A gene (MRE11) on chromosome 11q21.

Ataxia telangiectasia like disorder 2 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by developmental delay, ataxia, and sensorineural hearing loss. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PCNA gene located on chromosome 20p12. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with PCNA-related progressive neurodegenerative photosensitivity syndrome.

Tango2 related metabolic encephalopathy and arrhythmias is a syndrome, a type of autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by episodic metabolic degeneration affecting skeletal muscle, cardiac muscle, and the nervous system. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TANGO2 gene on chromosome 22q11. Moreover, it has exact synonyms TANGO2 deficiency and metabolic encephalomyopathic crises, recurrent, with rhabdomyolysis, cardiac arrhythmias, and neurodegeneration.

The neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by motor and language delay, ocular defects, and brain abnormalities is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is recognized for its onset in infancy or early childhood. This disorder is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder that emerges due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the INTS11 gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Primary progressive aphasia is a type of frontotemporal dementia defined as a frontotemporal dementia characterized by the progressive onset of language impairments and the gradual deterioration of these abilities over time. This condition is associated with atrophy of the language network of the brain, including the frontal, temporal, and parietal regions of the left hemisphere, and is caused by a loss of tissue (atrophy) in the area of the brain responsible for producing language.

Logopenic progressive aphasia is a type of primary progressive aphasia, which is defined as a primary progressive aphasia characterized by language disturbance, including difficulty making or understanding speech. Individuals affected by this condition have slow, hesitant speech due to difficulty retrieving the correct words, names, or numbers. It has exact synonyms: Logopenic primary progressive aphasia and logopenic variant PPA.

Progressive non-fluent aphasia is a type of primary progressive aphasia. It is defined as a primary progressive aphasia that is characterized by agrammatism, laborious speech, alexia, and agraphia, often accompanied by apraxia of speech. Moreover, it has the exact synonyms "Agrammatic variant of primary progressive aphasia" and "Nonfluent agrammatic PPA."

Semantic dementia is a type of primary progressive aphasia that is defined as a primary progressive aphasia characterized by the progressive, amodal, and profound loss of semantic knowledge and behavioral abnormalities, attributable to the degeneration of the anterior temporal lobes. It is also exactly synonymous with semantic variant PPA and semantic variant of primary progressive aphasia.

Corticobasal degeneration syndrome is a type of frontotemporal dementia defined as a frontotemporal dementia characterized by the loss of cognitive functions such as the ability to think, remember, or reason to the point that it interferes with a person's daily life and activities.

Organophosphate induced delayed polyneuropathy is a type of inflammatory and toxic neuropathy, which is characterized by a collection of neuropsychological symptoms associated with repeated organophosphate pesticide exposure as well as nerve agent exposure. Symptoms can appear weeks after exposure and include muscle weakness, anxiety, depression, psychosis, as well as cognitive and memory deficits. Moreover, it has an exact synonym, organophosphate induced delayed polyneuropathy.

Caroli syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, hepatic vascular diseases, bile duct diseases, and vein diseases. It is specifically linked to autosomal recessive inheritance and has a material basis tied to this form of inheritance.
