The disease predominantly affects the portal vein, liver, and bile ducts, indicating its location in these areas. Caroli syndrome is defined as a syndrome characterized by the presence of associated congenital hepatic fibrosis and is associated with autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease.

Harel Yoon syndrome is a type of syndrome that is both an autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive disease, indicating it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance as well as some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by delayed psychomotor development, intellectual disability, truncal hypotonia, spasticity, and peripheral neuropathy, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATAD3A gene on chromosome 1p36. Additionally, Harel Yoon syndrome has an exact synonym: Ocular anomalies-axonal neuropathy-developmental delay syndrome.

Neonatal lethal pontocerebellar hypoplasia hypotonia and respiratory insufficiency syndrome is a type of syndrome, autosomal recessive disease, and something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance as well as something whose existence starts during neonatal onset. It is characterized in infants by respiratory insufficiency and almost no spontaneous movement at birth, usually requiring mechanical ventilation and admission to the neonatal intensive care unit. This syndrome has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the ATAD3A gene on chromosome 1p36.33. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym PHRINL syndrome.

Vissers Bodmer syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by global developmental delay with variably impaired intellectual development, speech delay, motor delay, and behavioral abnormalities apparent from infancy. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CNOT1 gene on chromosome 16q21.

Holoprosencephaly 12 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a specific form of holoprosencephaly. This condition has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and its existence starts during congenital onset. It is characterized by an abnormal separation of the embryonic forebrain, resulting in dysmorphic facial features and, often but not always, impaired neurologic development, caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CNOT1 gene on chromosome 16q21. Additionally, holoprosencephaly 12 is exactly synonymous with holoprosencephaly-12 with or without pancreatic agenesis.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 10 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized clinically by length-dependent motor neuropathy primarily affecting the lower limbs. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the EMILIN1 gene located on chromosome 2p23.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 11 is a specific subtype of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy that typically begins in juveniles or young adults. This condition is characterized by the weakening and atrophy of distal limb muscles, predominantly affecting the lower limbs, which leads to instability in gait and difficulties in walking. The genetic basis for this condition is a heterozygous mutation in the SPTAN1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.

Autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 13 is a type of autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal dominant distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by distal muscle weakness and atrophy affecting both the upper and lower limbs, which results in difficulty walking and poor fine hand motor skills. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BSCL2 gene on chromosome 11q12.

Sarcoma with BCOR genetic alterations is a type of small cell sarcoma, which is defined as a small cell sarcoma characterized by the presence of small round or elongated malignant cells with a small amount of cytoplasm and the presence of BCOR genetic alterations. Additionally, it has the exact synonym BCOR-Rearranged Sarcoma.
BCOR ITD sarcoma, characterized by the presence of BCOR internal tandem duplications, is a type of sarcoma with BCOR genetic alterations. Its definition is a sarcoma with BCOR genetic alterations.

BCOR CCNB3 sarcoma is a type of sarcoma characterized by BCOR genetic alterations and is defined as a sarcoma with BCOR genetic alterations that is characterized by the presence of BCOR-CCNB3 fusion gene.

Childhood sarcoma with BCOR genetic alterations is a type of sarcoma characterized by BCOR genetic alterations and is defined as a sarcoma with BCOR genetic alterations that occurs during childhood. This type of sarcoma begins at least sometime during childhood onset.

Round cell sarcoma with EWSR1 non-ETS fusion is a type of small cell sarcoma that is defined by the presence of EWSR1 or FUS fusions involving partners unrelated to the ETS gene family. It has exact synonyms including Ewing-Like Sarcoma or Round Cell Sarcoma, and Round Cell Sarcoma with EWSR1::non-ETS Fusion.

Childhood round cell sarcoma with EWSR1 non-ETS fusion is a type of round cell sarcoma characterized by EWSR1-non-ETS fusion, and it typically begins in childhood. This condition is defined as a round cell sarcoma with EWSR1-non-ETS fusion that occurs during childhood, indicating its onset during some point in childhood.

Round cell sarcoma with EWSR1 NFATC2 gene fusion is a type of round cell sarcoma with EWSR1 non-ETS fusion. It is defined as a round cell sarcoma with EWSR1-non-ETS fusion that is characterized by the presence of EWSR1-NFATC2 gene fusion.

Round cell sarcoma with EWSR1 PATZ1 gene fusion is a specific type of round cell sarcoma with EWSR1 non-ETS fusion. It is defined as a round cell sarcoma with EWSR1-non-ETS fusion that is characterized by the presence of EWSR1-PATZ1 gene fusion.

Round cell sarcoma with FUS-NFATC2 gene fusion is a type of round cell sarcoma with EWSR1-non-ETS fusion, and it is defined as a round cell sarcoma with EWSR1-non-ETS fusion that is characterized by the presence of FUS-NFATC2 gene fusion.
B acute lymphoblastic leukemia with PAX5 P80R mutation is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma and is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma that is associated with PAX5 P80R mutation.

B acute lymphoblastic leukemia with DUX4 rearrangement is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma that is associated with DUX4 gene rearrangement.

Renal cell carcinoma with MIT translocations is a type of renal cell carcinoma characterized by papillary, alveolar, and nested growth patterns with clear and eosinophilic cells. This carcinoma is associated with translocations/gene fusions involving members of the MiT family of transcription factors. It is also known by its exact synonyms: MiT Family Translocation-Associated Renal Cell Carcinoma and MiT family translocation renal cell carcinoma.

TFEB rearranged renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma characterized by MiT translocations, specifically the chromosomal translocation t(6;11) which fuses the TFEB transcription factor gene on chromosome 6 with the MALAT1 gene on chromosome 11. This subtype of renal cell carcinoma is also precisely known by several exact synonyms including Renal Cell Carcinoma with t(6;11);(p21;q12); MALAT1-TFEB, Renal Cell Carcinoma with t(6;11);(p21;q12); MALAT1::TFEB, t(6;11) Renal Cell Carcinoma, and t(6;11);(p21;q12) Renal Cell Carcinoma.

Tfe3 rearranged renal cell carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma characterized by MiT translocations, notably involving different translocations with chromosome Xp11.2, leading to the creation of gene fusions involving the TFE3 gene. It is precisely defined as renal cell carcinoma associated with these specific translocations and gene fusions. This condition is exactly synonymous with Renal Cell Carcinoma Associated with Xp11.2 Translocations/TFE3 Gene Fusions and Xp11 Translocation Renal Cell Carcinoma.

Childhood renal cell carcinoma with MiT translocations is a type of renal cell carcinoma characterized by a TFE3 or TFEB-rearranged renal cell carcinoma that occurs during childhood. It is defined as a renal cell carcinoma with MiT translocations and is a condition whose existence at least starts during some childhood onset.

Poorly differentiated chordoma is a type of chordoma characterized by the loss of SMARCB1 expression and is composed of sheets or nests of malignant epithelioid cells with abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm.

Anaplastic sarcoma of the kidney is a type of kidney sarcoma, which is defined by a kidney sarcoma characterized by a proliferation of anaplastic spindle cells with bizarre, pleomorphic nuclei and atypical mitotic figures.

Childhood onset dystonia with optic atrophy and basal ganglia abnormalities is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, dystonia, and something that inherently has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, it is characterized as a condition whose existence begins during some point in childhood onset. This dystonia is defined by the onset of involuntary movements within the first decade of life, with its material basis rooted in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MECR gene on chromosome 1p35. Optic atrophy typically develops around the same time or slightly afterward. Furthermore, it is known by several exact synonyms including DYSTONIA 29, CHILDHOOD-ONSET, DYTOABG, MECR-related neurologic disorder, MEPAN syndrome, and Mitochondrial Enoyl CoA Reductase Protein-Associated Neurodegeneration.

Familial focal epilepsy with variable foci is a type of focal epilepsy and an autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a focal epilepsy characterized by focal seizures, where the seizure onset occurs in a discrete area of the brain, including the temporal, frontal, parietal, and occipital lobes. Notably, these focal seizures arise from different cortical regions in different family members. Additionally, familial focal epilepsy with variable foci has an exact synonym: DEPDC5-related epilepsy.

Familial focal epilepsy with variable foci 1 is a type of familial focal epilepsy with variable foci. It is defined as a familial focal epilepsy with variable foci characterized by focal seizures arising from different cortical regions in different family members. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DEPDC5 gene on chromosome 22q12.

Familial focal epilepsy with variable foci 2 is a type of familial focal epilepsy with variable foci. This specific condition is defined as a familial focal epilepsy with variable foci that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NPRL2 gene located on chromosome 3p21.

Familial focal epilepsy with variable foci 3 is a type of familial focal epilepsy with variable foci, characterized by having a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NPRL3 gene on chromosome 16p13.

Familial focal epilepsy with variable foci 4 is a type of familial focal epilepsy with variable foci, characterized by the onset of focal seizures in the first years of life. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SCN3A gene on chromosome 2q24.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 6 is a subtype of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy and also falls under the category of conditions that manifest congenitally, meaning its existence begins at or around birth. It is defined as an autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by the onset of distal muscle weakness in early infancy. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the REEP1 gene located on chromosome 2p11.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 7 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy, defined by an onset of lower leg weakness in the first decade. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VWA1 gene on chromosome 1p36.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 8 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by the onset of distal muscle weakness, primarily affecting the lower limbs, which leads to difficulty walking. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SORD gene located on chromosome 15q21. It is also exactly synonymous with SORDD and sorbitol dehydrogenase deficiency with peripheral neuropathy.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 9 is a subtype of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy and is characterized by juvenile onset. This condition is defined as an autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy marked by the onset during juvenile years of distal muscle weakness and atrophy, leading to difficulties in walking. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the COQ7 gene located on chromosome 16p12.

Autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy 10 is a type of autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy. It is defined as an autosomal recessive distal hereditary motor neuronopathy characterized by distal muscle weakness and atrophy predominantly affecting the lower limbs, leading to gait abnormalities. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VRK1 gene located on chromosome 14q32.

Intellectual developmental disorder with autistic features and language delay with or without seizures is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by global developmental delay, variable intellectual disability, impaired speech development, and behavioral abnormalities, most commonly on the autism spectrum. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TANC2 gene on chromosome 17q23. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, IDDALDS.

Fraser syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, specifically one that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by cryptophthalmos, syndactyly, ambiguous genitalia, laryngeal and genitourinary malformations, oral clefting, and mental retardation. This syndrome has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the FRAS1 gene on chromosome 4q21, the FREM2 gene on chromosome 13q13, or the GRIP1 gene on chromosome 12q14. Additionally, Fraser syndrome has an exact synonym: cryptophthalmos with other malformations.

Tietz syndrome is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of syndrome that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital profound bilateral sensorineural hearing loss and generalized albino-like hypopigmentation of skin, eyes, and hair, which is caused by a mutation in the MITF gene on chromosome 3p13. Additionally, Tietz syndrome is precisely known by several synonyms, including Tietz albinism-deafness syndrome, albinism-deafness of Tietz, and hypopigmentation/deafness of Tietz.

Agenesis of the corpus callosum with peripheral neuropathy is a type of disease that falls under several classifications: it is an autosomal recessive disease, a neurodegenerative disease, and is characterized by having at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. The condition is defined as a neurodegenerative disease with an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. It typically presents early on with severe sensory-motor polyneuropathy, a variable degree of agenesis of the corpus callosum, amyotrophy, hypotonia, and cognitive impairment. The disease is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC12A6 gene on chromosome 15q14. Additionally, agenesis of the corpus callosum with peripheral neuropathy is also known by several exact synonyms: Andermann syndrome, Charlevoix disease, and corpus callosum agenesis-neuronopathy syndrome, indicating its recognition and classification in various medical texts and studies under these names.

Progressive pseudorheumatoid arthropathy of childhood is a type of autosomal recessive disease and osteochondrodysplasia. It is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and its existence typically starts during childhood onset. Specifically, it is an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance with a typical onset around 3 years of age. It involves progressive severe degenerative joint disease, platyspondyly, and epiphyseal enlargement but lacks inflammatory joint disease, having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CHST3 gene on chromosome 10q22. Additionally, it has the exact synonym spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda-progressive arthropathy syndrome.

Schwartz Jampel Syndrome 1 is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by neuromyotonia and chondrodysplasia, which has its material basis in hypomorphic mutations in the HSPG2 gene located on chromosome 1p36. Schwartz Jampel Syndrome 1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including Aberfeld Syndrome, Burton Skeletal Dysplasia, Burton Syndrome, Catel-Hempel Syndrome, Catel-Hempel Type Dysostosis Enchondralis Metaepiphysaria, Schwartz-Jampel Syndrome Type 1, Schwartz-Jampel-Aberfeld Syndrome, Myotonic Chondrodystrophy, Myotonic Myopathy, Dwarfism, Chondrodystrophy, Ocular and Facial Anomalies, and Osteochondromuscular Dystrophy.

Renal coloboma syndrome is an autosomal dominant disease and a type of syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by optic nerve coloboma and renal disease that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PAX2 gene on chromosome 10q24. Renal coloboma syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including CAKUT with or without ocular abnormalities, coloboma of optic nerve with renal disease, congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract with or without ocular abnormalities, optic coloboma, vesicoureteral reflux and renal anomalies, papillo-renal syndrome or optic nerve coloboma with renal disease, papillorenal syndrome, and renal-coloboma syndrome with macular abnormalities.

Immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome, also known exactly as ICF syndrome, is a type of syndrome and autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a syndrome that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, ICF syndrome is defined by immunodeficiency, rearrangements in the vicinity of the centromeres of chromosomes 1, 9, and 16, and facial anomalies in most cases.

Immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome 1 is a type of immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome and has an exact synonym, ICF syndrome 1. It is defined as an immunodeficiency-centromeric instability-facial anomalies syndrome that is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, facial dysmorphism, and immunoglobulin deficiency of lymphocytes. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DNMT3B gene on chromosome 20q11.2.

Immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome 2 is a type of immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome. It is characterized by an immunodeficiency-centromeric instability-facial anomalies syndrome that manifests through autosomal recessive inheritance, facial dysmorphism, immunoglobulin deficiency leading to recurrent infections, and mental retardation. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ZBTB24 gene located on chromosome 6q21. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with ICF syndrome 2.

Immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome 3 is a type of immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome and is also known exactly as ICF syndrome 3. It is defined as an immunodeficiency-centromeric instability-facial anomalies syndrome characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition presents recurrent infections in childhood and variable dysmorphic facial features, which is caused by a homozygous mutation in the CDCA7 gene located on chromosome 2q31.

Immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome 4, also known precisely as ICF syndrome 4, is categorized under the broader term of immunodeficiency centromeric instability facial anomalies syndrome. It is defined as an immunodeficiency-centromeric instability-facial anomalies syndrome that manifests through autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by recurrent infections in childhood and can include a variety of dysmorphic facial features. The syndrome's material basis is found in either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the HELLS gene located on chromosome 10q23.

Severe combined immunodeficiency with sensitivity to ionizing radiation is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also classified under severe combined immunodeficiency. This condition inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency that is characterized by the absence of T cells and B cells, the presence of natural killer cells, a sensitivity to ionizing radiation, and is caused by a mutation in the DCLRE1C gene located on chromosome 10p13. Furthermore, this condition is recognized by several exact synonyms, including SCID due to DCLRE1C deficiency, SCID due to artemis deficiency, SCID, Athabascan type, SCID, Athabaskan type, Severe combined immunodeficiency due to DCLRE1C deficiency, Severe combined immunodeficiency due to artemis deficiency, Severe combined immunodeficiency, Athabascan type, Severe combined immunodeficiency, Athabaskan type, and artemis deficiency.

Severe combined immunodeficiency autosomal recessive T cell negative B cell negative NK cell positive is a form of severe combined immunodeficiency that falls within the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This condition is specifically characterized by the absence of T cells and B cells, alongside the presence of natural killer (NK) cells. It has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, with mutations in the RAG1 and RAG2 genes on chromosome 11p12 being the underlying cause. This immunodeficiency is also known by its exact synonyms: SCID due to complete RAG1-2 deficiency, Severe combined immunodeficiency due to complete RAG1-2 deficiency, and autosomal recessive T cell-negative, B-cell negative, NK cell-positive SCID.

Severe combined immunodeficiency autosomal recessive T cell-negative B cell-positive NK cell-positive, also precisely known as autosomal recessive T cell-negative, B-cell positive, NK cell-positive SCID, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of severe combined immunodeficiency. This condition inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by being T cell-negative, B cell-positive, and natural killer (NK) cell-positive and results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IL7R gene on chromosome 5p13 or the CD45 gene on chromosome 1q31.

Cenani Lenz syndactyly syndrome is a type of dysostosis, which is defined as a dysostosis characterized by syndactyly, malformation of the forearm and lower limb bones, renal hypoplasia or aplasia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LRP4 gene on chromosome 11p11. Additionally, Cenani Lenz syndactyly syndrome is exactly synonymous with syndactyly type 7.

Chromosome 5q deletion syndrome is a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome characterized by severe macrocytic anemia, erythroid hypoplasia in the bone marrow, and hypolobated micromegakaryocytes. This syndrome has a material basis in the somatic deletion of one allele of the RPS14, MIR145, MIR146A, and/or DDX41 genes on chromosome 5q. It is also exactly synonymous with 5q- syndrome, refractory macrocytic anemia due to 5q deletion, and myelodysplastic syndrome associated with isolated del(5q) chromosome abnormality.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex with muscular dystrophy is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by early childhood onset of progressive muscular dystrophy and blistering skin changes, and it has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLEC gene on chromosome 8q24. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including epidermolysis bullosa simplex and limb-girdle muscular dystrophy, as well as limb-girdle muscular dystrophy with epidermolysis bullosa simplex.

Autosomal dominant familial periodic fever is a type of disease that falls under several categories: it is an autosomal dominant disease, a primary immunodeficiency disease, and is characterized by having at least a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by recurrent fever, abdominal pain, localized tender skin lesions, arthralgia, and myalgia associated with skin, joint, ocular, and serosal inflammation, arising from a heterozygous mutation in the TNFRSF1A gene on chromosome 12p13. Furthermore, autosomal dominant familial periodic fever is known by several exact synonyms including FHF, FPF, TNF receptor associated periodic syndrome, TRAPS, familial Hibernian fever, hibernian fever, and tumor necrosis factor receptor associated periodic syndrome, indicating its diverse nomenclature within medical literature.

Sitosterolemia, also precisely known as phytosterolemia, is a type of autosomal recessive and intestinal disease. It is characterized by an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern that allows for unrestricted intestinal absorption of both cholesterol and plant-derived cholesterol-like molecules. This results in various symptoms including xanthomas, arthralgia, premature atherosclerosis, and hemolytic anemia with stomatocytosis and macrothrombocytopenia. The material basis for sitosterolemia is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in either the ABCG8 gene or the ABCG5 gene, both of which are located on chromosome 2p21.

Split hand foot malformation is a type of bone development disease that occurs at the intersection of the foot and hand. It is characterized by malformation of the central rays of the autopod, presenting with syndactyly, median clefts of the hands and feet, and aplasia and/or hypoplasia of the phalanges, metacarpals, and metatarsals. Additionally, some patients may also experience mental retardation, ectodermal and craniofacial findings, and orofacial clefting. This condition is also known by its exact synonyms, lobster-claw deformity and split-hand deformity.

Split hand foot malformation 1 (SHFD1 or SHFM1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of split hand foot malformation. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is defined by a split-hand/foot malformation that arises from contiguous gene mutations caused by deletion, duplication, or rearrangement of chromosome 7q21.3. This involves the DSS1, DLX5, and DLX6 genes along with possible regulatory elements in the region. Furthermore, it affects an area that represents an intersection of the foot and hand.

Split hand foot malformation 5 is a type of split hand foot malformation and is also a type of condition that occurs at the intersection of the foot and hand. It is defined as a split-hand/foot malformation that has its material basis in deletions in the chromosome region 2q31. Furthermore, Split hand foot malformation 5 is exactly synonymous with SHFM5.

Split hand foot malformation 4 (SHFM4) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of split hand foot malformation. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is located at the intersection of the foot and hand, indicating its manifestation in these areas. Furthermore, SHFM4 is defined by a split-hand/foot malformation that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the TP63 gene on chromosome 3q28.

Split hand foot malformation 1 with sensorineural hearing loss is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also categorized under split hand foot malformation. This condition is defined by a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is located at the intersection of the hand and foot. It is characterized by the presence of split-hand/foot malformation combined with sensorineural hearing impairment, which arises from a homozygous mutation in the DLX5 gene on chromosome 7q21. Additionally, this condition is precisely known by two exact synonyms: SHFM1D and congenital deafness with split hands and feet.

Split hand foot malformation 3 (SHFM3), also known as chromosome 10q24 duplication syndrome and distal limb deficiencies with micrognathia, is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome and a specific form of split hand foot malformation. It is characterized by an intersection of conditions that have a material basis in at least some chromosome and some duplication, specifically a contiguous gene duplication syndrome on chromosome 10q24. Moreover, it is associated with diseases located at the intersection of the foot and hand. The definition of SHFM3 emphasizes that it is a split-hand/foot malformation with its material basis in this specific chromosomal duplication.

Split hand foot malformation 6 (SHFM6) is a type of split hand foot malformation and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and typically affects the intersection of the foot and hand. The disease is defined by a split-hand/foot malformation that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the WNT10B gene located on chromosome 12q13.

Split hand foot malformation 2 (SHFM2) is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, which is a specific form of split hand foot malformation. It is characterized by a disease that has its material basis in X-linked inheritance and is located at the intersection of the foot and hand. Furthermore, SHFM2 is defined by a variation in the chromosome region Xq26.

Familial isolated deficiency of vitamin E is a type of vitamin metabolic disorder and also falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a vitamin metabolic disorder characterized by progressive spino-cerebellar ataxia, loss of proprioception, areflexia, and a marked deficiency in vitamin E, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TTPA gene on chromosome 8q12. This condition is exactly synonymous with ataxia with isolated vitamin E deficiency and familial isolated vitamin E deficiency.

CINCA syndrome is a type of disease that is not only autosomal dominant but also autoimmune. It is characterized by neonatal onset of cutaneous symptoms, chronic meningitis, and joint manifestations accompanied by recurrent fever and inflammation. This condition stems from a heterozygous mutation in the NLRP3 gene located on chromosome 1q. Furthermore, CINCA syndrome is known by several exact synonyms: IOMID syndrome, NOMID syndrome, Prieur-Griscelli syndrome, chronic infantile neurological cutaneous articular syndrome, chronic neurologic cutaneous and articular syndrome, cryopyrin-associated periodic syndrome 3, infantile-onset multisystem inflammatory disease, and neonatal-onset multisystem inflammatory disease.

Corticosteroid binding globulin deficiency, which is also precisely known as CBG deficiency and transcortin deficiency, is a type of monogenic disease, adrenal gland disease, and represents a condition that inherently has a genetic basis. It is specifically characterized by decreased levels of serum corticosteroid-binding globulin and cortisol, which in some instances leads to hypo- or hypertension, and muscle fatigue. This condition is caused by either heterozygous or homozygous mutations in the SERPINA6 gene located on chromosome 14q32.

D bifunctional protein deficiency is a type of peroxisomal disease and is also a type of condition that has its basis in some structural variant. It is defined as a peroxisomal disease characterized by severe cases that may involve infantile-onset of hypotonia, seizures, and abnormal facial features, with most affected individuals dying before age 2 years. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the HSD17B4 gene located on chromosome 5q2.

Silverman Handmaker type dyssegmental dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by short-limbed dwarfism, anisospondyly, and neonatal lethality. This condition results from autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding perlecan (HSPG2) on chromosome 1p36.

Myoclonic dystonia is a type of dystonia which is defined as a dystonia characterized by myoclonic jerks affecting mostly proximal muscles and dystonia, usually manifesting as torticollis or writer's cramp. It typically responds to alcohol and has an onset in the first or second decade of life.

Myoclonic dystonia 11 is a type of myoclonic dystonia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by myoclonic jerks primarily affecting proximal muscles. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically a heterozygous mutation in the epsilon-sarcoglycan gene (SGCE) on chromosome 7q21.

Myoclonic dystonia 15 is a type of myoclonic dystonia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by jerky movements of the upper limbs, hands, and axial muscles. This condition specifically has its material basis in an autosomal dominant inheritance of variation in the chromosome region 18p11, indicating that it is a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Myoclonic dystonia 26 is a type of myoclonic dystonia and a form of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the onset of myoclonic jerks affecting the upper limbs, progressing to dystonia with predominant involvement of the craniocervical regions. It is specifically associated with a heterozygous mutation in the KCTD17 gene on chromosome 22q12, indicating that it at least has its material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Torsion dystonia 13 is a type of dystonia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a dystonia characterized by focal or segmental dystonia with involvement of the cranial, cervical, or upper limbs, and it has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of variation in the chromosome region 1p36.32-p36.13.

Torsion dystonia 2 is a type of dystonia and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by initially affecting the distal limbs and later involving the neck, orofacial, and craniocervical regions. This condition is rooted in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically through homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the hippocalcin (HPCA) gene located on chromosome 1p35.

Torsion dystonia 6 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of generalized dystonia. It is characterized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of torsion dystonia 6 elaborates it as a generalized dystonia that is marked by early-onset generalized dystonia, typically involving the craniocervical region with spasmodic dysphonia. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the THAP domain containing 1 gene (THAP1) on chromosome 8p11.

Torsion dystonia 7 is a type of autosomal dominant and focal dystonia, which also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a focal dystonia, predominantly characterized by cervical dystonia, and has its material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of variation in the chromosome region 18p.

Torsion dystonia 4 is a type of dystonia, which is an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is characterized as a dystonia that involves progressive laryngeal and cervical dystonia, beginning in the second to third decade of life, and may later affect other muscles, such as those in the neck or limbs. The basis for this disease is an autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the tubulin beta 4A class IVa (TUBB4A) gene located on chromosome 19p13. This indicates that torsion dystonia 4 is also a type of disorder that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Torsion dystonia 17 is a type of dystonia and an autosomal recessive disease, defined by progressive dystonia, dysphonia, dysarthria, and neck torticollis. It fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically due to variation in the chromosome region 20p11.2-q13.12.

Dystonia 5 is a type of dystonia characterized by childhood-onset dystonia that responds to low doses of levodopa (L-dopa) and may be associated with parkinsonism at an older age. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding GTP cyclohydrolase 1 (GCH1) on chromosome 14q22.3. This condition is considered both an autosomal dominant disease, due to its inheritance pattern, and an autosomal recessive disease. Additionally, it is described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance and also in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Dystonia 9 is a type of dystonia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that arises due to at least having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is driven by factors like alcohol. Specifically, it is defined as a dystonia characterized by paroxysmal choreoathetosis and progressive spastic paraplegia, where episodes are often triggered by alcohol, fatigue, or emotional stress. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 2 member 1 (SLC2A1) gene located on chromosome 1p34.

Childhood onset GLUT1 deficiency syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and dystonia. It is characterized by a condition that begins during childhood onset and has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is a dystonia that is characterized by paroxysmal exercise-induced dyskinesia involving transient abnormal involuntary movements in the exercised limbs. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 2 member 1 (SLC2A1) gene on chromosome 1p34.

Dystonia 21 is a type of dystonia and an autosomal dominant disease, characterized by a specific kind of dystonia that manifests as late onset pure torsion dystonia. It is defined by its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, particularly through variation in the chromosome region 2q14.3-q21.3. This condition is also described as a type of disorder that fundamentally requires autosomal dominant inheritance for its manifestation.

Paroxysmal nonkinesigenic dyskinesia 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of dystonia. It is also classified as a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is driven by factors such as alcohol. This condition is defined as a dystonia characterized by attacks of dystonic or choreathetotic movements precipitated by stress, fatigue, coffee or alcohol intake, or menstruation, and it has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of variation in the chromosome region 2q31.
